{"title_page": "S\u00e2hib Ata", "text_new": "{{One source|date=July 2011}}\n'''Fakhr al-Din Ali''', better known as '''S\u00e2hib Ata''' or '''S\u00e2hip Ata''', held a number of high offices at the court of the [[Sultanate of Rum]] from the 1250s until his death in 1288. He was the dominant personality in [[Anatolia]] after the death of the [[Pervane|Pervane Mu\u2019in al-Din Suleyman]] in 1277. He is perhaps best remembered for the charitable foundations he established in cities across the [[Sultanate of Rum]].\n\nFakhr al-Din's sons, the ''[[Sahib Ataids]]'', established a short-lived principality centered in [[Afyonkarahisar]], which the neighboring [[Germiyanids]] absorbed ''ca.'' 1341.\n\n==Monuments==\nFakhr al-Din left many architectural monuments. In 1271 he funded the construction of the [[G\u00f6k Medrese]] in [[Sivas]].<ref>J.M. Rogers, \u201cThe \u00c7ifte Minare Medrese at Erzurum and the G\u00f6k Medrese at Sivas: A Contribution to the History of Style in the Seljuk Architecture of 13th Century Turkey\u201d ''Anatolian Studies'', Vol. 15. (1965), pp. 66.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sahib Ata}}\n[[Category:1288 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of the Sultanate of Rum]]\n[[Category:History of Afyonkarahisar Province]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n\n\n{{turkey-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{One source|date=July 2011}}\n'''Fakhr al-Din Ali''', better known as '''S\u00e2hib Ata''' or '''S\u00e2hip Ata''', held a number of high offices at the court of the [[Sultanate of Rum]] from the 1250s until his death in 1288. He was the dominant personality in [[Anatolia]] after the death of the [[Pervane|Pervane Mu\u2019in al-Din Suleyman]] in 1277. He is perhaps best remembered for the charitable foundations he established in cities across the [[Sultanate of Rum]].\n\nFakhr al-Din\u2019s sons, the ''[[Sahib Ataids]]'', established a short-lived principality centered in [[Afyonkarahisar]], which the neighboring [[Germiyanids]] absorbed ''ca.'' 1341.\n\n==Monuments==\nFakhr al-Din left many architectural monuments. In 1271 he funded the construction of the [[G\u00f6k Medrese]] in [[Sivas]].<ref>J.M. Rogers, \u201cThe \u00c7ifte Minare Medrese at Erzurum and the G\u00f6k Medrese at Sivas: A Contribution to the History of Style in the Seljuk Architecture of 13th Century Turkey\u201d ''Anatolian Studies'', Vol. 15. (1965), pp. 66.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sahib Ata}}\n[[Category:1288 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of the Sultanate of Rum]]\n[[Category:History of Afyonkarahisar Province]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n\n\n{{turkey-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%C3%A2hib_Ata"}
