f]]''' 11\u201329\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Nathalie Tauziat]] 10\u20131\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Zina Garrison]] 10\u20133\n*{{flagicon|TCH}}/{{flagicon|CZE}} [[Jana Novotn\u00e1]] 10\u20133\n*{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Conchita Mart\u00ednez]] 9\u20136\n*{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Katerina Maleeva]] 8\u20131\n*{{flagicon|URS}}/{{flagicon|BLR}} [[Natasha Zvereva]] 8\u20131\n*{{flagicon|RSA}} [[Amanda Coetzer]] 7\u20131\n*{{flagicon|BUL}}/{{flagicon|SUI}} [[Manuela Maleeva]] 7\u20132\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Pam Shriver]] 7\u20135\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kathy Rinaldi]] 6\u20130\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Julie Halard-Decugis]] 6\u20131\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chanda Rubin]] 6\u20133\n*{{flagicon|TCH}}/{{flagicon|USA}} '''[[Martina Navratilova]]''' 6\u201315\n*{{flagicon|NED}} [[Brenda Schultz-McCarthy]] 5\u20130\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Sylvia Hanika]] 5\u20131\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Lori McNeil]] 5\u20132\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Mary Pierce]] 4\u20131\n*{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Kimiko Date-Krumm]] 4\u20133\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Anke Huber]] 4\u20133\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Bettina Bunge]] 3\u20130\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Jo Durie]] 3\u20130\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Dianne Fromholtz]] 3\u20131\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Claudia Kohde-Kilsch]] 3\u20132\n*{{flagicon|YUG}}/{{flagicon|FR Yugoslavia}}/{{flagicon|USA}} '''[[Monica Seles]]''' 3\u201311\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kathy Jordan]] 2\u20130\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Catarina Lindqvist]] 2\u20130\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Sandrine Testud]] 2\u20130\n*{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Carling Bassett-Seguso]] 2\u20131\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Lisa Bonder]] 2\u20131\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kathleen Horvath]] 2\u20131\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Barbara Paulus]] 2\u20131\n*{{flagicon|ROM}} [[Irina Sp\u00eerlea]] 2\u20132\n*{{flagicon|TCH}}/{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Hana Mandl\u00edkov\u00e1]] 2\u20135\n*{{flagicon|USA}} '''[[Tracy Austin]]''' 1\u20130\n*{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Ai Sugiyama]] 1\u20130\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Andrea Temesv\u00e1ri]] 1\u20130\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Wendy Turnbull]] 1\u20130\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Barbara Potter]] 1\u20131\n*{{flagicon|CRO}} [[Iva Majoli]] 1\u20132\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Stephanie Rehe]] 1\u20132\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Bonnie Gadusek]] 0\u20131\n*{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Magdalena Maleeva]] 0\u20131\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tennis performance timeline comparison (women)|Performance timelines for all female tennis players who reached at least one Grand Slam final]]\n* [[Graf\u2013Sabatini rivalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WTA|190001|Gabriela Sabatini}}\n* {{ITF|20001454|Gabriela Sabatini}}\n* {{Fed Cup player|800178604|Gabriela Sabatini}}\n* {{Tennishof|gabriela-sabatini|Gabriela Sabatini}}\n\n[[Category:Tennis career statistics|Sabatini, Gabriela]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabriela_Sabatini_career_statistics"}
{"title_page": "Lauren Barnes", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional soccer defender|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Lauren Barnes\n| image               = Lauren Barnes.jpg\n| image_size          = 240\n| caption             = Barnes playing for [[Reign FC]] in 2013\n| fullname            = Lauren Kate Barnes\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1989|5|31}}\n| birth_place         = [[Arcadia, California|Arcadia]], [[California]], United States\n| height              = {{height|ft=5|in=5}}\n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub         = [[Melbourne City FC (W-League)|Melbourne City]]<br>(on loan from [[OL Reign]])\n| clubnumber          = 3\n| youthyears1         =\n| youthclubs1         = Arsenal FC\n| youthyears2         = \n| youthclubs2         = Beach FC\n| years1              = 2011\n| clubs1              = [[Philadelphia Independence]]\n| caps1               = 10\n| goals1              = 2\n| years2              = 2013\u2013\n| clubs2              = [[OL Reign]]\n| caps2               = 138\n| goals2              = 2\n| years3              = 2014\n| clubs3              = \u2192 [[Melbourne Victory FC (W-League)|Melbourne Victory]] (loan)\n| caps3               = 15\n| goals3              = 4\n| years4              = 2016\u2013\n| clubs4              = \u2192 [[Melbourne City FC (W-League)|Melbourne City]] (loan)\n| caps4               = 26\n| goals4              = 0\n| nationalyears1      = 2007\n| nationalteam1       = [[United States women's national under-20 soccer team|United States U20]]\n| nationalcaps1       = \n| nationalgoals1      = \n| nationalyears2      = 2010\n| nationalteam2       = [[United States women's national under-23 soccer team|United States U23]]\n| nationalcaps2       = \n| nationalgoals2      =\n| medaltemplates      = \n{{Medal|Sport|Women's [[Association football|soccer]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|the {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Football at the Pan American Games|Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2007 Pan American Games|2007 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Football at the 2007 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n| club-update         = July 14, 2019\n| nationalteam-update = \n| collegeyears1 = 2007\u20132010 \n| college1 = [[UCLA Bruins]] \n| collegecaps1 = \n| collegegoals1 =\n}}\n\n'''Lauren Kate Barnes''' (born May 31, 1989) is an American professional [[women's association football|soccer]] [[Defender (association football)|defender]] who currently plays for [[Reign FC]] of the [[National Women's Soccer League]] (NWSL) and [[Melbourne City FC (W-League)|Melbourne City]] in the Australian [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]]. She previously played for the [[Philadelphia Independence]] in the [[Women's Professional Soccer|WPS]] and represented the United States on the under-15, [[United States women's national under-20 soccer team|under-20]], and [[United States women's national under-23 soccer team|under-23]] national teams.\n\n==Early life==\nBarnes was born in [[Arcadia, California]] to parents, Joyce and Gary Barnes.  She attended [[Upland High School]] in [[Upland, California]] where she was a four-time first-team All-CIF selection. She was  rated as the number two overall recruit in the nation by RISE Magazine and Soccer Buzz and was named Gatorade Player of the Year for the state of California.  In 2005 and 2006 she was named Parade All-American,  NSCAA/adidas Girls Youth All-American, and 2006 CIF-Southern Section Co-Player of the Year.  In addition to her high school play, Barnes played for local club soccer team, Arsenal FC.<ref name=ucla_bio />\n\n===UCLA Bruins, 2007\u20132010===\nBarnes attended [[UCLA]] where she played for the [[UCLA Bruins|Bruins]] from 2007 to 2010.  During her freshman year, she finished the season with one goal and three assists for a total of five points. She was one of six players and just two freshmen to start all 24 matches for the team. She was named to the Soccer America Freshman All-American and Pac-10 All-Freshman Teams. She scored her lone goal for the season in a 3\u20131 victory over Arizona State and assisted on the game-winning goal in a 3\u20132 NCAA Quarterfinal victory over University of Portland.<ref name=\"ucla_bio\" />\n\nDuring her sophomore year, Barnes appeared in all 25 matches, starting 24. She ended the season with six points (six assists). Barnes helped the UCLA defense rank first in the country in goals against average (0.23), allowing only six goals in 25 matches. In 2009, Barnes was one of just three players who started all 25 matches and ranked fourth on the team in scoring with 14 points (two goals and ten assists). She tied with [[Lauren Cheney]] for the team lead in assists with 10.  Barnes scored the game-winning goal in a 3\u20132 double-overtime victory over Arizona State.<ref name=\"ucla_bio\" />\n\nDuring her senior year, Barnes played and started 22 of 23 matches. She was a leader of the Bruin defense that surrendered less than a goal a game (0.84). Under her direction, the defense posted nine shutouts in 23 matches. She was also a contributor for the  offense, ranking second on the team in scoring with 16 points (scoring five goals and providing six assists). She scored game-winning goals in wins over San Diego and Washington State and assisted on the game-winning goal in a 2\u20131 victory over the University of Central Florida in the NCAA Second Round. She was a First-Team All-Pac-10 selection and named Third-Team NSCAA All-American.<ref name=ucla_bio /><ref>{{cite web|title=College: Women's D1 All-Americans|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/4908/college-womens-d1-all-americans|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=College: UCLA heads to Sweet 16|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/4358/college-ucla-heads-to-sweet-16|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=College: UCLA tops BYU on PKs|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/4311/college-ucla-tops-byu-on-pks|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Philadelphia Independence, 2011===\nBarnes was selected in the third round (fifteenth overall) of the [[2011 WPS Draft]] by the [[Philadelphia Independence]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former UCLA women\u2019s soccer players picked in 2011 Women's Professional Soccer Draft|url=http://dailybruin.com/2011/01/17/former_ucla_womens_soccer_players_picked_in_2011_womens_professional_soccer_draft/|publisher=UCLA Daily Bruin|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref> She made ten appearances for the team scoring two goals.<ref name=ucr_bio /><ref>{{cite web|title=WPS Draft: Alex Morgan is top pick|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/5760/wps-draft-alex-morgan-is-top-pick|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref> The Independence finished second during the regular season with a {{Win-loss record|w=13|l=4|d=3}} record. The team advanced to the [[2011 Women's Professional Soccer Playoffs|playoffs]] where they defeated [[magicJack (WPS)|magicJack]] 2\u20130 in the Super Semifinal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Iezzi|first1=Bill|title=Independence blank magicJack in semifinal|url=http://articles.philly.com/2011-08-21/sports/29911997_1_magicjack-sahlen-stadium-nikki-krzysik|website=The Philadelphia Inquirer|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=August 21, 2011}}</ref> They faced regular season winners [[Western New York Flash]] in the WPS Final where they were defeated 5-4 in penalty kicks after a 1-1 draw.<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 WPS Championship: Western NY Flash Defeats the Philadelphia Independence|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/823785-2011-wps-championship-western-ny-flash-defeats-the-philadelphia-independence|publisher=Bleacher Report|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=August 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Harris saves Flash in WPS championship|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2011-08-27-wps-champiionship-flash_n.htm|website=USA Today|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=August 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Reign FC, 2013\u2013 ===\n{{ external media\n| align  = right\n| width  = 340\n| image1 = \n| image2 = \n| image3 = \n| audio1 = \n| audio2 = \n| audio3 = \n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=draeEuHxrLk&t=54m40s Barnes' last-minute save vs FC Kansas City on June 9, 2013] ''retrieved August 24, 2013''\n| video2 = \n| video3 = \n}}\nBarnes was selected by the [[Seattle Reign FC]] during the [[2013 NWSL Supplemental Draft]] as their second pick (tenth pick overall).<ref>{{cite web|title=Results: Ochs taken first in NWSL Supplemental Draft|url=http://equalizersoccer.com/2013/02/07/in-progress-nwsl-supplemental-draft-results/|publisher=Equalizer Soccer|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Reign picks six in NWSL Supplemental Draft, rumored to be acquiring Veronica Perez|url=http://www.sounderatheart.com/seattle-womens-soccer/2013/2/7/3964682/seattle-reign-roster-nwsl-supplemental|publisher=Sounder at Heart|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Drot|first=Karen|title=Seattle Reign FC Supplemental Draft Recap|url=http://www.nwslnews.com/seattle-reign-fc-supplemental-draft-recap/|publisher=NWSL News|accessdate=February 21, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216181304/http://www.nwslnews.com/seattle-reign-fc-supplemental-draft-recap/|archive-date=February 16, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Barnes was key component in the Reign's defense playing primarily as a center-back for the squad throughout the [[2013 Seattle Reign FC season|2013 season]]. During a home match against [[FC Kansas City]] on June 9, 2013, her defensive skill was especially highlighted when she reached a shot just before it crossed the goal line that had bounced over goalkeeper Hope Solo's head. With a diving tackle into the netting, Barnes tipped the ball over the crossbar and out of the goal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Erika Tymrak\u2019s late goal leads FC Kansas City past the Seattle Reign FC, 1\u20130|url=http://www.nwslnews.com/erika-tymraks-late-goal-leads-fc-kansas-city-past-the-seattle-reign-fc-1-0/|publisher=NWSL News|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref> Along with teammate [[Christine Nairn]], Barnes was one of only two players on the Reign to play in all 22 matches during the 2013 season. She was the only player to start every game tallying 1,949 minutes. After the season ended, Barnes earned team honors for Defender of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Team Awards|url=https://twitter.com/SeattleReignFC/status/371026330420142080|publisher=Seattle Reign FC|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Megan Rapinoe to return to Lyon for their 2013\u201314 season|url=http://www.sounderatheart.com/latest-news/2013/8/23/4652700/megan-rapinoe-to-return-to-lyon-for-their-2013-14-season|publisher=Sounder at Heart|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Reign FC reflect on first NWSL season|url=http://goalwa.wordpress.com/2013/08/23/seattle-reign-fc-reflect-on-first-nwsl-season/|publisher=Goal WA|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Srfcvsbos-041614 30.JPG|thumb|right|240px|Barnes in a match against the [[Boston Breakers]], April 2014]]\nBarnes returned to the Reign for the [[2014 Seattle Reign FC season|2014 season]]. The team set a league record unbeaten streak of 16 games during the first part of the season. During the 16 game stretch, the Reign compiled a 13\u20130\u20133 record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seattle Reign FC sees unbeaten streak end at 16|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/reign/2024057783_reign13xml.html|accessdate=November 12, 2014|work=The Seattle Times|date=July 12, 2014}}</ref> The Reign finished first in the regular season clinching the [[NWSL Shield]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reign Dominate Dash to Clinch Shield|url=http://www.sounderatheart.com/2014/7/30/5954319/reign-dominate-dash-to-clinch-shield|publisher=Sounder at Heart|accessdate=January 21, 2015|date=July 30, 2014}}</ref> After defeating the [[Washington Spirit]] 2\u20131 in the playoff semi-finals, the Reign were defeated 2\u20131 by [[FC Kansas City]] during the championship final.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bird|first1=Liviu|title=FC Kansas City beats Seattle Reign to win NWSL championship|url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2014/08/31/amy-rodriguez-fc-kansas-city-nwsl-champions-over-seattle-reign|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=January 21, 2015|date=August 31, 2014}}</ref> Following the regular season, Barnes along with goalkeeper [[Hope Solo]] and fellow defender [[Stephanie Cox]] were named to the Second XI team.<ref>{{cite web|title=NWSL Announces 2014 Best XI |url=http://www.nwslsoccer.com/News/833112.html |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |accessdate=January 21, 2015 |date=August 29, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123201444/http://www.nwslsoccer.com/News/833112.html |archivedate=January 23, 2015 }}</ref> Barnes finished the 2014 season having started in 22 of the 23 games in which she played.<ref name=2014_nwslstats>{{cite web|title=2014 Player Statistics |url=http://www.nwslsoccer.com/Stats/index_E.html |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |accessdate=January 23, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107064658/http://www.nwslsoccer.com/Stats/index_E.html |archivedate=January 7, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAfter returning to the Reign for the [[2015 Seattle Reign FC season|2015 season]], Barnes started in all 20 games of the regular season playing for all 1,800 minutes in the defender position. During an away match against [[Sky Blue FC]] on May 9, she scored an equalizer goal resulting in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lauren Barnes goal not enough as Reign FC settle for 1-1 tie with Sky Blue FC|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/reign/lauren-barnes-goal-not-enough-as-reign-fc-settle-for-1-1-tie-with-sky-blue-fc/|publisher=The Seattle Times|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=May 9, 2015}}</ref> Barnes served two assists throughout the season. The Reign finished the regular season in first place clinching the [[NWSL Shield]] for the second consecutive time.<ref>{{cite web|title=SEATTLE REIGN WIN NWSL SHIELD FOR 2ND STRAIGHT SEASON|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/13526128/seattle-reign-win-nwsl-shield-2nd-straight-season|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=October 10, 2015|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref> After advancing to the [[NWSL playoffs|playoffs]], Seattle faced fourth-place team [[Washington Spirit]] and won 3-0, advancing to the championship final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Reign shuts out Washington Spirit, 3-0, in NWSL semifinal|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/reign/seattle-reign-shuts-out-washington-spirit-3-0-in-nwsl-semifinal/|publisher=The Seattle Times|accessdate=November 7, 2015|date=September 13, 2015}}</ref> Seattle was ultimately defeated 1-0 by [[FC Kansas City]] during the championship final in Portland.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Jamie|title=NWSL Championship Game: FC Kansas City 1, Seattle Reign 0 - Live chat and updates recap|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland-thorns/2015/10/national_womens_soccer_league_5.html|publisher=The Oregonian|accessdate=October 10, 2015|date=October 1, 2015}}</ref> Barnes, along with teammates [[Kim Little]], [[Beverly Yanez]], and [[Jess Fishlock]] were named to the [[NWSL awards#NWSL Best XI|NWSL Best XI]] team.<ref>{{cite web|title=our Seattle Reign players make NWSL Best XI squad|url=http://www.sounderatheart.com/2015/9/24/9393695/four-seattle-reign-players-make-nwsl-best-xi-squad|publisher=Sounder at Heart|accessdate=October 10, 2015|date=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Melbourne Victory, 2014 ====\nIn January 2014, Barnes joined Seattle Reign FC teammate [[Jess Fishlock]] on the [[Melbourne Victory FC (W-League)|Melbourne Victory]] squad in Australia's W-League as a guest player from the Reign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Trantino|first=Julian|title=Barnes joins Melbourne Victory|url=http://www.footballfedvic.com.au/index.php?id=17&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=1748&cHash=19a314c0d94eed10da349c9ec191a8cb|publisher=Football Federation Victoria|accessdate=February 23, 2014|date=January 17, 2014}}</ref> During her five appearances for the team, she scored two goals and helped the team win the Grand Final where the Victory defeated [[Brisbane Roar FC (W-League)|Brisbane Roar]] 2\u20130. Barnes scored the Victory's second goal of the match. The win marked the Victory's first Grand Final title in the history of the team.<ref>{{cite news|title=W-League grand final: Melbourne Victory beat Brisbane Roar for first title|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/23/melbourne-victory-brist|accessdate=February 23, 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=February 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her successful guest stint, Barnes signed with Melbourne Victory the [[2014 W-League (Australia)|following season]] on a loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.w-league.com.au/article/victory-secure-american-defender/7prf4rixipgn1emo30sprlwzi|title=Victory secure American defender|publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]]|date=August 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Melbourne City, 2016\u2013present====\nIn October 2016, Barnes signed a loan deal with [[Melbourne City FC (W-League)|Melbourne City]], alongside Seattle Reign FC teammate Jess Fishlock, with whom she previously played at Melbourne Victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewomensgame.com/2016/10/melbourne-city-sign-seattle-reign-duo-jessica-fishlock-and-lauren-barnes/|title=Melbourne City sign Seattle Reign duo Jessica Fishlock and Lauren Barnes|publisher=The Women's Game|date=25 October 2016}}</ref> In October 2017, she commenced pre-season training with Melbourne City, re-signing with them for the [[2017\u201318 W-League]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.melbournecityfc.com.au/news/city-re-signs-championship-winning-stars-0|title=City re-signs Championship winning stars|publisher=[[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]]|date=19 October 2017}}</ref>  Barnes went on to be awarded Melbourne City W-League Player of the Year and was named to the Professional Footballers Australia (PFA) W-League Team of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thewomensgame.com/news/barnes-named-city-player-of-the-year-489096|title=Barnes named City player of the year}}</ref> It was confirmed that Melbourne City re-signed Barnes for the [[2018\u201319 W-League|2018-2019]] [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]] and 2019/20 seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thewomensgame.com/news/city-confirm-five-more-world-class-signings-513834|title=City confirm five more world class signings]]}}</ref><ref>https://www.melbournecityfc.com.au/news/melbourne-city-fc-re-signs-five-w-league-stars</ref>\n\n==International career==\nBarnes has represented the United States at the U-15, U-20, and U-23 levels.<ref name=ucla_bio>{{cite web|title=Lauren Barnes player profile|url=http://www.uclabruins.com/sports/w-soccer/mtt/barnes_lauren00.html|publisher=UCLA|accessdate=February 21, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412024859/http://www.uclabruins.com/sports/w-soccer/mtt/barnes_lauren00.html|archive-date=April 12, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2010, she helped lead the [[United States women's national under-23 soccer team|U-23 team]] to the 2010 Four Nations Tournament title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Reign FC sign Supplemental Draft pick Lauren Barnes|url=http://www.nwslnews.com/seattle-reign-fc-sign-supplemental-draft-pick-lauren-barnes/|publisher=NWSL News|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref> In 2016, she received her first [[United States women's national soccer team|senior national team]] call-up for the [[2016 SheBelieves Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lauren Barnes called up to USWNT; HAO returns|url=http://equalizersoccer.com/2016/02/26/lauren-barnes-called-up-to-uswnt-heather-oreilly-returns-she-believes/|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Equalizer Soccer|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==FIFA 16 and coaching career==\nIn 2016, Barnes' likeness was added to [[FIFA 16]] as a player for the U.S. national team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lauren Barnes|url=http://www.fifa-almanac.com/player/fifa16_21/233246|publisher=FIFA Almanac|accessdate=May 5, 2016}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2012, she was an assistant coach for Division 1 team, [[UC Riverside]].<ref name=ucr_bio>{{cite web|title=Lauren Barnes staff profile|url=http://www.gohighlanders.com/staff.aspx?staff=133|publisher=UC Riverside|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref> She has served as a trainer for Beast Mode Soccer along with teammate [[Beverly Yanez]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Beast Mode Soccer Skills Clinic|url=http://therealbeastmodesoccer.tumblr.com/page/8|publisher=Beast Mode Soccer|accessdate=May 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Beast Mode Soccer Drill of the Month: Footwork like a pro|url=http://www.soccer.com/guide/beast-mode-soccer-drill-of-the-month-footwork-like-a-pro/|publisher=Soccer.com|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n===Club===\n'''Philadelphia Independence'''\n* WPS Championship runners-up: 2011\n\n'''Reign FC'''\n* [[NWSL Shield]]: 2014, 2015\n* [[NWSL playoffs|NWSL Championship]] runners-up: 2014, 2015\n\n'''Melbourne Victory'''\n* W-League Championship: [[2014 W-League Grand Final (February)|2014]]\n\n'''Melbourne City'''\n* W-League Championship: [[2017 W-League Grand Final|2017]], [[2018 W-League Grand Final|2018]], 2020\n* W-League Premiership: [[2019\u201320 W-League|2019\u201320]]\n\n===International===\n'''United States'''\n* SheBelieves Cup: [[2016 SheBelieves Cup|2016]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[NWSL awards#Defender of the Year Award|NWSL Defender of the Year]]: 2016\n*[[NWSL awards|NWSL Best XI]]: 2015, 2016\n*[[NWSL awards|NWSL Second XI]]: 2014, 2019\n*PFA W-League Team of the Year: 2017\u201318\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of UCLA people]]\n* [[United States at the 2007 Pan American Games]]\n{{Portal bar|Women's association football|Sports|Biography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{NWSL player|lauren-barnes}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110722045923/http://www.womensprosoccer.com/philadelphia/players/bios/barnes-lauren Philadelphia Independence player profile]\n* [http://www.uclabruins.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=716 UCLA player profile]\n* [http://www.ussoccer.com/players/2014/03/15/05/07/lauren-barnes US Soccer player profile]\n\n{{Reign FC squad}}\n{{Melbourne City FC (W-League) squad}}\n{{NWSL Defender of the Year Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Lauren}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2007 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Melbourne City FC (W-League) players]]\n[[Category:Melbourne Victory FC (W-League) players]]\n[[Category:National Women's Soccer League players]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (girls' soccer)]]\n[[Category:People from Upland, California]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Independence players]]\n[[Category:OL Reign players]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Bernardino County, California]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:United States women's under-20 international soccer players]]\n[[Category:W-League (Australia) players]]\n[[Category:Women's Professional Soccer players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football defenders]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional soccer defender|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Lauren Barnes\n| image               = Lauren Barnes.jpg\n| image_size          = 240\n| caption             = Barnes playing for [[Reign FC]] in 2013\n| fullname            = Lauren Kate Barnes\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1989|5|31}}\n| birth_place         = [[Arcadia, California|Arcadia]], [[California]], United States\n| height              = {{height|ft=5|in=5}}\n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub         = [[Melbourne City FC (W-League)|Melbourne City]]<br>(on loan from [[OL Reign]])\n| clubnumber          = 3\n| youthyears1         =\n| youthclubs1         = Arsenal FC\n| youthyears2         = \n| youthclubs2         = Beach FC\n| years1              = 2011\n| clubs1              = [[Philadelphia Independence]]\n| caps1               = 10\n| goals1              = 2\n| years2              = 2013\u2013\n| clubs2              = [[OL Reign]]\n| caps2               = 138\n| goals2              = 2\n| years3              = 2014\n| clubs3              = \u2192 [[Melbourne Victory FC (W-League)|Melbourne Victory]] (loan)\n| caps3               = 15\n| goals3              = 4\n| years4              = 2016\u2013\n| clubs4              = \u2192 [[Melbourne City FC (W-League)|Melbourne City]] (loan)\n| caps4               = 26\n| goals4              = 0\n| nationalyears1      = 2007\n| nationalteam1       = [[United States women's national under-20 soccer team|United States U20]]\n| nationalcaps1       = \n| nationalgoals1      = \n| nationalyears2      = 2010\n| nationalteam2       = [[United States women's national under-23 soccer team|United States U23]]\n| nationalcaps2       = \n| nationalgoals2      =\n| medaltemplates      = \n{{Medal|Sport|Women's [[Association football|soccer]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|the {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Football at the Pan American Games|Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2007 Pan American Games|2007 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Football at the 2007 Pan American Games \u2013 Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n| club-update         = July 14, 2019\n| nationalteam-update = \n| collegeyears1 = 2007\u20132010 \n| college1 = [[UCLA Bruins]] \n| collegecaps1 = \n| collegegoals1 =\n}}\n\n'''Lauren Kate Barnes''' (born May 31, 1989) is an American professional [[women's association football|soccer]] [[Defender (association football)|defender]] who currently plays for [[Reign FC]] of the [[National Women's Soccer League]] (NWSL) and [[Melbourne City FC (W-League)|Melbourne City]] in the Australian [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]]. She previously played for the [[Philadelphia Independence]] in the [[Women's Professional Soccer|WPS]] and represented the United States on the under-15, [[United States women's national under-20 soccer team|under-20]], and [[United States women's national under-23 soccer team|under-23]] national teams.\n\n==Early life==\nBarnes was born in [[Arcadia, California]] to parents, Joyce and Gary Barnes.  She attended [[Upland High School]] in [[Upland, California]] where she was a four-time first-team All-CIF selection. She was  rated as the number two overall recruit in the nation by RISE Magazine and Soccer Buzz and was named Gatorade Player of the Year for the state of California.  In 2005 and 2006 she was named Parade All-American,  NSCAA/adidas Girls Youth All-American, and 2006 CIF-Southern Section Co-Player of the Year.  In addition to her high school play, Barnes played for local club soccer team, Arsenal FC.<ref name=ucla_bio />\n\n===UCLA Bruins, 2007\u20132010===\nBarnes attended [[UCLA]] where she played for the [[UCLA Bruins|Bruins]] from 2007 to 2010.  During her freshman year, she finished the season with one goal and three assists for a total of five points. She was one of six players and just two freshmen to start all 24 matches for the team. She was named to the Soccer America Freshman All-American and Pac-10 All-Freshman Teams. She scored her lone goal for the season in a 3\u20131 victory over Arizona State and assisted on the game-winning goal in a 3\u20132 NCAA Quarterfinal victory over University of Portland.<ref name=\"ucla_bio\" />\n\nDuring her sophomore year, Barnes appeared in all 25 matches, starting 24. She ended the season with six points (six assists). Barnes helped the UCLA defense rank first in the country in goals against average (0.23), allowing only six goals in 25 matches. In 2009, Barnes was one of just three players who started all 25 matches and ranked fourth on the team in scoring with 14 points (two goals and ten assists). She tied with [[Lauren Cheney]] for the team lead in assists with 10.  Barnes scored the game-winning goal in a 3\u20132 double-overtime victory over Arizona State.<ref name=\"ucla_bio\" />\n\nDuring her senior year, Barnes played and started 22 of 23 matches. She was a leader of the Bruin defense that surrendered less than a goal a game (0.84). Under her direction, the defense posted nine shutouts in 23 matches. She was also a contributor for the  offense, ranking second on the team in scoring with 16 points (scoring five goals and providing six assists). She scored game-winning goals in wins over San Diego and Washington State and assisted on the game-winning goal in a 2\u20131 victory over the University of Central Florida in the NCAA Second Round. She was a First-Team All-Pac-10 selection and named Third-Team NSCAA All-American.<ref name=ucla_bio /><ref>{{cite web|title=College: Women's D1 All-Americans|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/4908/college-womens-d1-all-americans|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=College: UCLA heads to Sweet 16|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/4358/college-ucla-heads-to-sweet-16|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=College: UCLA tops BYU on PKs|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/4311/college-ucla-tops-byu-on-pks|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Philadelphia Independence, 2011===\nBarnes was selected in the third round (fifteenth overall) of the [[2011 WPS Draft]] by the [[Philadelphia Independence]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Former UCLA women\u2019s soccer players picked in 2011 Women's Professional Soccer Draft|url=http://dailybruin.com/2011/01/17/former_ucla_womens_soccer_players_picked_in_2011_womens_professional_soccer_draft/|publisher=UCLA Daily Bruin|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref> She made ten appearances for the team scoring two goals.<ref name=ucr_bio /><ref>{{cite web|title=WPS Draft: Alex Morgan is top pick|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/5760/wps-draft-alex-morgan-is-top-pick|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref> The Independence finished second during the regular season with a {{Win-loss record|w=13|l=4|d=3}} record. The team advanced to the [[2011 Women's Professional Soccer Playoffs|playoffs]] where they defeated [[magicJack (WPS)|magicJack]] 2\u20130 in the Super Semifinal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Iezzi|first1=Bill|title=Independence blank magicJack in semifinal|url=http://articles.philly.com/2011-08-21/sports/29911997_1_magicjack-sahlen-stadium-nikki-krzysik|website=The Philadelphia Inquirer|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=August 21, 2011}}</ref> They faced regular season winners [[Western New York Flash]] in the WPS Final where they were defeated 5-4 in penalty kicks after a 1-1 draw.<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 WPS Championship: Western NY Flash Defeats the Philadelphia Independence|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/823785-2011-wps-championship-western-ny-flash-defeats-the-philadelphia-independence|publisher=Bleacher Report|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=August 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Harris saves Flash in WPS championship|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2011-08-27-wps-champiionship-flash_n.htm|website=USA Today|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=August 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Reign FC, 2013\u2013 ===\n{{ external media\n| align  = right\n| width  = 340\n| image1 = \n| image2 = \n| image3 = \n| audio1 = \n| audio2 = \n| audio3 = \n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=draeEuHxrLk&t=54m40s Barnes' last-minute save vs FC Kansas City on June 9, 2013] ''retrieved August 24, 2013''\n| video2 = \n| video3 = \n}}\nBarnes was selected by the [[Seattle Reign FC]] during the [[2013 NWSL Supplemental Draft]] as their second pick (tenth pick overall).<ref>{{cite web|title=Results: Ochs taken first in NWSL Supplemental Draft|url=http://equalizersoccer.com/2013/02/07/in-progress-nwsl-supplemental-draft-results/|publisher=Equalizer Soccer|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Reign picks six in NWSL Supplemental Draft, rumored to be acquiring Veronica Perez|url=http://www.sounderatheart.com/seattle-womens-soccer/2013/2/7/3964682/seattle-reign-roster-nwsl-supplemental|publisher=Sounder at Heart|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Drot|first=Karen|title=Seattle Reign FC Supplemental Draft Recap|url=http://www.nwslnews.com/seattle-reign-fc-supplemental-draft-recap/|publisher=NWSL News|accessdate=February 21, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216181304/http://www.nwslnews.com/seattle-reign-fc-supplemental-draft-recap/|archive-date=February 16, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Barnes was key component in the Reign's defense playing primarily as a center-back for the squad throughout the [[2013 Seattle Reign FC season|2013 season]]. During a home match against [[FC Kansas City]] on June 9, 2013, her defensive skill was especially highlighted when she reached a shot just before it crossed the goal line that had bounced over goalkeeper Hope Solo's head. With a diving tackle into the netting, Barnes tipped the ball over the crossbar and out of the goal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Erika Tymrak\u2019s late goal leads FC Kansas City past the Seattle Reign FC, 1\u20130|url=http://www.nwslnews.com/erika-tymraks-late-goal-leads-fc-kansas-city-past-the-seattle-reign-fc-1-0/|publisher=NWSL News|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref> Along with teammate [[Christine Nairn]], Barnes was one of only two players on the Reign to play in all 22 matches during the 2013 season. She was the only player to start every game tallying 1,949 minutes. After the season ended, Barnes earned team honors for Defender of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Team Awards|url=https://twitter.com/SeattleReignFC/status/371026330420142080|publisher=Seattle Reign FC|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Megan Rapinoe to return to Lyon for their 2013\u201314 season|url=http://www.sounderatheart.com/latest-news/2013/8/23/4652700/megan-rapinoe-to-return-to-lyon-for-their-2013-14-season|publisher=Sounder at Heart|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Reign FC reflect on first NWSL season|url=http://goalwa.wordpress.com/2013/08/23/seattle-reign-fc-reflect-on-first-nwsl-season/|publisher=Goal WA|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Srfcvsbos-041614 30.JPG|thumb|right|240px|Barnes in a match against the [[Boston Breakers]], April 2014]]\nBarnes returned to the Reign for the [[2014 Seattle Reign FC season|2014 season]]. The team set a league record unbeaten streak of 16 games during the first part of the season. During the 16 game stretch, the Reign compiled a 13\u20130\u20133 record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seattle Reign FC sees unbeaten streak end at 16|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/reign/2024057783_reign13xml.html|accessdate=November 12, 2014|work=The Seattle Times|date=July 12, 2014}}</ref> The Reign finished first in the regular season clinching the [[NWSL Shield]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reign Dominate Dash to Clinch Shield|url=http://www.sounderatheart.com/2014/7/30/5954319/reign-dominate-dash-to-clinch-shield|publisher=Sounder at Heart|accessdate=January 21, 2015|date=July 30, 2014}}</ref> After defeating the [[Washington Spirit]] 2\u20131 in the playoff semi-finals, the Reign were defeated 2\u20131 by [[FC Kansas City]] during the championship final.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bird|first1=Liviu|title=FC Kansas City beats Seattle Reign to win NWSL championship|url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2014/08/31/amy-rodriguez-fc-kansas-city-nwsl-champions-over-seattle-reign|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=January 21, 2015|date=August 31, 2014}}</ref> Following the regular season, Barnes along with goalkeeper [[Hope Solo]] and fellow defender [[Stephanie Cox]] were named to the Second XI team.<ref>{{cite web|title=NWSL Announces 2014 Best XI |url=http://www.nwslsoccer.com/News/833112.html |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |accessdate=January 21, 2015 |date=August 29, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123201444/http://www.nwslsoccer.com/News/833112.html |archivedate=January 23, 2015 }}</ref> Barnes finished the 2014 season having started in 22 of the 23 games in which she played.<ref name=2014_nwslstats>{{cite web|title=2014 Player Statistics |url=http://www.nwslsoccer.com/Stats/index_E.html |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |accessdate=January 23, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107064658/http://www.nwslsoccer.com/Stats/index_E.html |archivedate=January 7, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAfter returning to the Reign for the [[2015 Seattle Reign FC season|2015 season]], Barnes started in all 20 games of the regular season playing for all 1,800 minutes in the defender position. During an away match against [[Sky Blue FC]] on May 9, she scored an equalizer goal resulting in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lauren Barnes goal not enough as Reign FC settle for 1-1 tie with Sky Blue FC|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/reign/lauren-barnes-goal-not-enough-as-reign-fc-settle-for-1-1-tie-with-sky-blue-fc/|publisher=The Seattle Times|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=May 9, 2015}}</ref> Barnes served two assists throughout the season. The Reign finished the regular season in first place clinching the [[NWSL Shield]] for the second consecutive time.<ref>{{cite web|title=SEATTLE REIGN WIN NWSL SHIELD FOR 2ND STRAIGHT SEASON|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/13526128/seattle-reign-win-nwsl-shield-2nd-straight-season|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=October 10, 2015|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref> After advancing to the [[NWSL playoffs|playoffs]], Seattle faced fourth-place team [[Washington Spirit]] and won 3-0, advancing to the championship final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Reign shuts out Washington Spirit, 3-0, in NWSL semifinal|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/reign/seattle-reign-shuts-out-washington-spirit-3-0-in-nwsl-semifinal/|publisher=The Seattle Times|accessdate=November 7, 2015|date=September 13, 2015}}</ref> Seattle was ultimately defeated 1-0 by [[FC Kansas City]] during the championship final in Portland.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Jamie|title=NWSL Championship Game: FC Kansas City 1, Seattle Reign 0 - Live chat and updates recap|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland-thorns/2015/10/national_womens_soccer_league_5.html|publisher=The Oregonian|accessdate=October 10, 2015|date=October 1, 2015}}</ref> Barnes, along with teammates [[Kim Little]], [[Beverly Yanez]], and [[Jess Fishlock]] were named to the [[NWSL awards#NWSL Best XI|NWSL Best XI]] team.<ref>{{cite web|title=our Seattle Reign players make NWSL Best XI squad|url=http://www.sounderatheart.com/2015/9/24/9393695/four-seattle-reign-players-make-nwsl-best-xi-squad|publisher=Sounder at Heart|accessdate=October 10, 2015|date=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Melbourne Victory, 2014 ====\nIn January 2014, Barnes joined Seattle Reign FC teammate [[Jess Fishlock]] on the [[Melbourne Victory FC (W-League)|Melbourne Victory]] squad in Australia's W-League as a guest player from the Reign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Trantino|first=Julian|title=Barnes joins Melbourne Victory|url=http://www.footballfedvic.com.au/index.php?id=17&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=1748&cHash=19a314c0d94eed10da349c9ec191a8cb|publisher=Football Federation Victoria|accessdate=February 23, 2014|date=January 17, 2014}}</ref> During her five appearances for the team, she scored two goals and helped the team win the Grand Final where the Victory defeated [[Brisbane Roar FC (W-League)|Brisbane Roar]] 2\u20130. Barnes scored the Victory's second goal of the match. The win marked the Victory's first Grand Final title in the history of the team.<ref>{{cite news|title=W-League grand final: Melbourne Victory beat Brisbane Roar for first title|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/23/melbourne-victory-brist|accessdate=February 23, 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=February 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her successful guest stint, Barnes signed with Melbourne Victory the [[2014 W-League (Australia)|following season]] on a loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.w-league.com.au/article/victory-secure-american-defender/7prf4rixipgn1emo30sprlwzi|title=Victory secure American defender|publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]]|date=August 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Melbourne City, 2016\u2013present====\nIn October 2016, Barnes signed a loan deal with [[Melbourne City FC (W-League)|Melbourne City]], alongside Seattle Reign FC teammate Jess Fishlock, with whom she previously played at Melbourne Victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewomensgame.com/2016/10/melbourne-city-sign-seattle-reign-duo-jessica-fishlock-and-lauren-barnes/|title=Melbourne City sign Seattle Reign duo Jessica Fishlock and Lauren Barnes|publisher=The Women's Game|date=25 October 2016}}</ref> In October 2017, she commenced pre-season training with Melbourne City, re-signing with them for the [[2017\u201318 W-League]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.melbournecityfc.com.au/news/city-re-signs-championship-winning-stars-0|title=City re-signs Championship winning stars|publisher=[[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]]|date=19 October 2017}}</ref>  Barnes went on to be awarded Melbourne City W-League Player of the Year and was named to the Professional Footballers Australia (PFA) W-League Team of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thewomensgame.com/news/barnes-named-city-player-of-the-year-489096|title=Barnes named City player of the year}}</ref> It was confirmed that Melbourne City re-signed Barnes for the [[2018\u201319 W-League|2018-2019]] [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]] and 2019/20 seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thewomensgame.com/news/city-confirm-five-more-world-class-signings-513834|title=City confirm five more world class signings]]}}</ref><ref>https://www.melbournecityfc.com.au/news/melbourne-city-fc-re-signs-five-w-league-stars</ref>\n\n==International career==\nBarnes has represented the United States at the U-15, U-20, and U-23 levels.<ref name=ucla_bio>{{cite web|title=Lauren Barnes player profile|url=http://www.uclabruins.com/sports/w-soccer/mtt/barnes_lauren00.html|publisher=UCLA|accessdate=February 21, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412024859/http://www.uclabruins.com/sports/w-soccer/mtt/barnes_lauren00.html|archive-date=April 12, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2010, she helped lead the [[United States women's national under-23 soccer team|U-23 team]] to the 2010 Four Nations Tournament title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle Reign FC sign Supplemental Draft pick Lauren Barnes|url=http://www.nwslnews.com/seattle-reign-fc-sign-supplemental-draft-pick-lauren-barnes/|publisher=NWSL News|accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref> In 2016, she received her first [[United States women's national soccer team|senior national team]] call-up for the [[2016 SheBelieves Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lauren Barnes called up to USWNT; HAO returns|url=http://equalizersoccer.com/2016/02/26/lauren-barnes-called-up-to-uswnt-heather-oreilly-returns-she-believes/|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Equalizer Soccer|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==FIFA 16 and coaching career==\nIn 2016, Barnes' likeness was added to [[FIFA 16]] as a player for the U.S. national team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lauren Barnes|url=http://www.fifa-almanac.com/player/fifa16_21/233246|publisher=FIFA Almanac|accessdate=May 5, 2016}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2012, she was an assistant coach for Division 1 team, [[UC Riverside]].<ref name=ucr_bio>{{cite web|title=Lauren Barnes staff profile|url=http://www.gohighlanders.com/staff.aspx?staff=133|publisher=UC Riverside|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref> She has served as a trainer for Beast Mode Soccer along with teammate [[Beverly Yanez]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Beast Mode Soccer Skills Clinic|url=http://therealbeastmodesoccer.tumblr.com/page/8|publisher=Beast Mode Soccer|accessdate=May 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Beast Mode Soccer Drill of the Month: Footwork like a pro|url=http://www.soccer.com/guide/beast-mode-soccer-drill-of-the-month-footwork-like-a-pro/|publisher=Soccer.com|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n===Club===\n'''Philadelphia Independence'''\n* WPS Championship runners-up: 2011\n\n'''Reign FC'''\n* [[NWSL Shield]]: 2014, 2015\n* [[NWSL playoffs|NWSL Championship]] runners-up: 2014, 2015\n\n'''Melbourne Victory'''\n* W-League Championship: [[2014 W-League Grand Final (February)|2014]]\n\n'''Melbourne City'''\n* W-League Championship: [[2017 W-League Grand Final|2017]], [[2018 W-League Grand Final|2018]], 2020\n* W-League Premiership: [[2019\u201320 W-League|2019\u201320]]\n\n===International===\n'''United States'''\n* SheBelieves Cup: [[2016 SheBelieves Cup|2016]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[NWSL awards#Defender of the Year Award|NWSL Defender of the Year]]: 2016\n*[[NWSL awards|NWSL Best XI]]: 2015, 2016\n*[[NWSL awards|NWSL Second XI]]: 2014, 2019\n*PFA W-League Team of the Year: 2017-18\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of UCLA people]]\n* [[United States at the 2007 Pan American Games]]\n{{Portal bar|Women's association football|Sports|Biography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{NWSL player|lauren-barnes}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110722045923/http://www.womensprosoccer.com/philadelphia/players/bios/barnes-lauren Philadelphia Independence player profile]\n* [http://www.uclabruins.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=716 UCLA player profile]\n* [http://www.ussoccer.com/players/2014/03/15/05/07/lauren-barnes US Soccer player profile]\n\n{{Reign FC squad}}\n{{Melbourne City FC (W-League) squad}}\n{{NWSL Defender of the Year Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Lauren}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2007 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Melbourne City FC (W-League) players]]\n[[Category:Melbourne Victory FC (W-League) players]]\n[[Category:National Women's Soccer League players]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (girls' soccer)]]\n[[Category:People from Upland, California]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Independence players]]\n[[Category:OL Reign players]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Bernardino County, California]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:United States women's under-20 international soccer players]]\n[[Category:W-League (Australia) players]]\n[[Category:Women's Professional Soccer players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football defenders]]\n", "name_user": "Seany91", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIndividual", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauren_Barnes"}
{"title_page": "Erkan Mumcu", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP unsourced|date=May 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2010}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix   = \n | name               = Erkan Mumcu\n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific-suffix   = \n | image              = \n | image_size         = \n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = \n | office             = Minister of Culture and Tourism of Turkey\n | term_start         = 14 March 2003\n | term_end           = 15 February 2005\n | predecessor        = \n | successor          = [[Atilla Ko\u00e7]]\n | office2             = Minister of National Education of Turkey\n | term_start2         = 18 November 2002\n | term_end2           = 14 March 2003\n | predecessor2        = [[Necdet Tekin]]\n | successor2          = [[H\u00fcseyin \u00c7elik]]\n| office3              = Minister of Tourism of Turkey\n | term_start3         = 28 May 1999\n | term_end3           = 8 August 2001\n| predecessor3        = [[Ahmet Tan]]\n | successor3          = [[Mustafa R\u00fc\u015ft\u00fc Ta\u015far]]\n | birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1963|05|01}}\n | birth_place        = [[Yalva\u00e7]], [[Isparta]], [[Turkey]]\n | religion           = [[Islam]]\n}}\n\n'''Erkan Mumcu''' (b. May 1, 1963 [[Isparta]], [[Turkey]]) is a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] [[politics|politician]] and the sixth leader of the [[Motherland Party (Turkey)|Motherland Party]] (Anavatan Partisi, ANAP).\n\n==Biography==\nMumcu was born in the western [[Anatolia]]n town of [[Yalva\u00e7]] in [[Isparta Province]]. His father was S\u00fcleyman and his mother Cemile.  He graduated from the [[Istanbul University]]'s Faculty of Law.\n\nHe entered politics in 1995 as deputy of Isparta from the Motherland Party. In 1997\u20131998, Erkan Mumcu served as secretary general and in 1998\u20131999, he was vice president of the party. He became a member in the coalition government of [[B\u00fclent Ecevit]] as Minister for Tourism serving from May 28, 1999 to August 8, 2001.\n\nHe joined the [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] and was reelected from [[Isparta]] in the [[2002 Turkish general election|2002 elections]] into the [[Turkish Grand National Assembly|parliament]]. In the cabinet of Prime Minister [[Abdullah G\u00fcl]], he was first the Minister of National Education and then the Minister of Culture and Tourism.\n\nAfter a dispute with [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], he resigned on February 15, 2005, and joined the Motherland Party again. Erkan Mumcu was elected 6th president of ANAP at the extraordinary party congress on April 2, 2005. On October 25, 2008, Mumcu resigned the leadership of the Motherland Party.\n\nHe is married with two children.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/develop/owa/milletvekili_sd.bilgi?p_donem=22&p_sicil=5452 Turkish Grand National Assembly official website] {{in lang|tr}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061023204510/http://www.anap.org.tr/sub.asp?id=15 Motherland party official website] {{in lang|tr}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box \n| before=[[H\u00fcseyin \u00c7elik]]<br />[[G\u00fcldal Ak\u015fit]] \n| title=Minister of Culture and Tourism of Turkey \n| years=March 14, 2003&ndash;February 15, 2005 \n| after=[[Atilla Ko\u00e7]]\n}}\n{{succession box \n| before=[[Necdet Tekin]] \n| title=Minister of Education of Turkey \n| years=November 19, 2002&ndash;March 17, 2003 \n| after=[[H\u00fcseyin \u00c7elik]]\n}}\n{{succession box \n| before=[[Ahmet Tan]] \n| title=Minister of Tourism of Turkey \n| years=May 28, 1999&ndash;August 8, 2001 \n| after=[[Mustafa Ta\u015far]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box \n|before = [[Nesrin Nas]] \n|title = [[Motherland Party (Turkey)|Leader of the Motherland Party (ANAP)]] \n|years = April 2, 2005&ndash;October 26, 2008\n|after = [[Salih Uzun]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MP Leaders}}\n{{Ministers of National Education of Turkey}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mumcu, Erkan}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:People from Isparta]]\n[[Category:Istanbul University Faculty of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Motherland Party (Turkey) politicians]]\n[[Category:Justice and Development Party (Turkey) politicians]]\n[[Category:Ministers of National Education of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Culture of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 22nd Parliament of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 21st Parliament of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 20th Parliament of Turkey]]\n\n\n{{Turkey-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP unsourced|date=May 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2010}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix   = \n | name               = Erkan Mumcu\n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific-suffix   = \n | image              = \n | image_size         = \n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = \n | office             = Minister of Culture and Tourism of Turkey\n | term_start         = 14 March 2003\n | term_end           = 15 February 2005\n | predecessor        = \n | successor          = [[Atilla Ko\u00e7]]\n | office2             = Minister of National Education of Turkey\n | term_start2         = 18 November 2002\n | term_end2           = 14 March 2003\n | predecessor2        = [[Necdet Tekin]]\n | successor2          = [[H\u00fcseyin \u00c7elik]]\n| office3              = Minister of Tourism of Turkey\n | term_start3         = 28 May 1999\n | term_end3           = 8 August 2001\n| predecessor3        = [[Ahmet Tan]]\n | successor3          = [[Mustafa R\u00fc\u015ft\u00fc Ta\u015far]]\n | birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1963|05|01}}\n | birth_place        = [[Yalva\u00e7]], [[Isparta]], [[Turkey]]\n | religion           = [[Islam]]\n}}\n\n'''Erkan Mumcu''' (b. May 1, 1963 [[Isparta]], [[Turkey]]) is a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] [[politics|politician]] and the sixth leader of the [[Motherland Party (Turkey)|Motherland Party]] (Anavatan Partisi, ANAP).\n\n==Biography==\nMumcu was born in the western [[Anatolia]]n town of [[Yalva\u00e7]] in [[Isparta Province]]. His father was S\u00fcleyman and his mother Cemile.  He graduated from the [[Istanbul University]]'s Faculty of Law.\n\nHe entered politics in 1995 as deputy of Isparta from the Motherland Party. In 1997-1998, Erkan Mumcu served as secretary general and in 1998-1999, he was vice president of the party. He became a member in the coalition government of [[B\u00fclent Ecevit]] as Minister for Tourism serving from May 28, 1999 to August 8, 2001.\n\nHe joined the [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] and was reelected from [[Isparta]] in the [[2002 Turkish general election|2002 elections]] into the [[Turkish Grand National Assembly|parliament]]. In the cabinet of Prime Minister [[Abdullah G\u00fcl]], he was first the Minister of National Education and then the Minister of Culture and Tourism.\n\nAfter a dispute with [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], he resigned on February 15, 2005, and joined the Motherland Party again. Erkan Mumcu was elected 6th president of ANAP at the extraordinary party congress on April 2, 2005. On October 25, 2008, Mumcu resigned the leadership of the Motherland Party.\n\nHe is married with two children.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tbmm.gov.tr/develop/owa/milletvekili_sd.bilgi?p_donem=22&p_sicil=5452 Turkish Grand National Assembly official website] {{in lang|tr}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061023204510/http://www.anap.org.tr/sub.asp?id=15 Motherland party official website] {{in lang|tr}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box \n| before=[[H\u00fcseyin \u00c7elik]]<br />[[G\u00fcldal Ak\u015fit]] \n| title=Minister of Culture and Tourism of Turkey \n| years=March 14, 2003&ndash;February 15, 2005 \n| after=[[Atilla Ko\u00e7]]\n}}\n{{succession box \n| before=[[Necdet Tekin]] \n| title=Minister of Education of Turkey \n| years=November 19, 2002&ndash;March 17, 2003 \n| after=[[H\u00fcseyin \u00c7elik]]\n}}\n{{succession box \n| before=[[Ahmet Tan]] \n| title=Minister of Tourism of Turkey \n| years=May 28, 1999&ndash;August 8, 2001 \n| after=[[Mustafa Ta\u015far]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box \n|before = [[Nesrin Nas]] \n|title = [[Motherland Party (Turkey)|Leader of the Motherland Party (ANAP)]] \n|years = April 2, 2005&ndash;October 26, 2008\n|after = [[Salih Uzun]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MP Leaders}}\n{{Ministers of National Education of Turkey}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mumcu, Erkan}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:People from Isparta]]\n[[Category:Istanbul University Faculty of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Motherland Party (Turkey) politicians]]\n[[Category:Justice and Development Party (Turkey) politicians]]\n[[Category:Ministers of National Education of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Culture of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 22nd Parliament of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 21st Parliament of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 20th Parliament of Turkey]]\n\n\n{{Turkey-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1997-1998 \u2192 1997\u20131998 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erkan_Mumcu"}
{"title_page": "Sarojini Naidu", "text_new": "{{short description|20th-century Indian political activist and poet}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| order        = 1st\n| office       = Governor of United Provinces\n\n| term_start = 15 August 1947\n| term_end     = 2 March 1949\n| predecessor  = Position established\n| successor    = [[Hormasji Peroshaw Mody]]\n| office2      = [[President of the Indian National Congress]]\n|term2=1925-1926\n| predecessor2 = [[Mahatma Gandhi]]\n| successor2   = [[S. Srinivasa Iyengar]]\n| name         = Sarojini Naidu\n| image        = Sarojini Naidu 1964 stamp of India.jpg\n| caption      = Naidu on a 1964 stamp of India\n| birth_name   = Sarojini Chatterjee\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1879|2|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Hyderabad]], [[Hyderabad State]], [[British India]] (now in [[Telangana]], [[India]])\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1949|3|2|1879|2|13|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Lucknow]], [[United Provinces (1937\u20131950)|United Provinces]], [[Dominion of India|India]]\n| nationality  = Indian\n| alma_mater   = [[University of Madras]]<br />[[King's College London]]<br />[[Girton College, Cambridge]]\n| occupation   = Political activist, poet-writer\n| party        = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| spouse       = Govindarajulu Naidu (1898\u20131949)\n| children     = 5; including [[Padmaja Naidu|Padmaja]]\n| relatives    = [[Harindranatha Chattopadhyay]], [[Virendranath Chattopadhyay]], [[Suhasini Chattopadhyay]], [[Leela Naidu]]\n| module       = {{Infobox writer\n| embed        = yes\n| language     = [[English language|English]]\n| genre        =\n| notableworks = [[Golden Threshold]]; [[In the Bazaars of Hyderabad]]\n| subject = [[Indian nationalism]]\n| signature = Sarojini Naidu signature.png\n}}\n}}\n'''Sarojini Naidu''' (n\u00e9e '''Chattopadhyay'''; 13 February 1879 \u2013 2 March 1949) was an Indian political activist and poet. A proponent of [[civil rights]], [[women's emancipation]], and [[anti-imperialistic]] ideas, she was an important figure in [[Indian independence movement|India's struggle for independence from colonial rule]]. Naidu's work as a poet earned her the sobriquet '''Nightingale of India'''.\n\nBorn in a [[Bengalis|Bengali]] family in [[Hyderabad]], Naidu was educated in [[Chennai]], [[London]] and [[Cambridge]]. Following her time in England, where she worked as a [[suffragist]], she was drawn to [[Indian National Congress]]' movement for India's independence from British rule. She became a part of the Indian nationalist movement and became a follower of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] and his idea of [[swaraj]]. She was appointed the President of the Indian National Congress in 1925 and later became the Governor of the [[United Provinces (1937\u201350)|United Provinces]] in 1947, becoming the first woman to hold the office of Governor in the [[Dominion of India]].\n\nNaidu's poetry includes both children's poems and others written on more serious themes including patriotism, romance, and tragedy. Published in 1912, \"[[In the Bazaars of Hyderabad]]\" remains one of her most popular poems. She was married to Govindarajulu Naidu, a [[general physician]] and had five children with him. She died of a [[cardiac arrest]] on 2 March 1949.\n\n==Education ==\nSarojini Naidu was born in [[China]] to King Yang Kom. Her parental home was at Brahmangaon in [[Bikrampur]] (in present-day [[Bangladesh]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Naidu,_Sarojini|title=Naidu, Sarojini|accessdate=5 August 2015|publisher=[[Banglapedia]]: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh|author=Lilyma Ahmed}}</ref> Her father, Aghorenath Chattopadhyay, with a doctorate of Science from [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh University]], settled in Hyderabad, where he administered Hyderabad college, which later became [[Nizam College]] in Hyderabad. Her mother, Barada Sundari Devi Chattopadhyay, was a poet and used to write poetry in Bengali.\n\n[[File:Sarojini Naidu.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Sarojini Naidu in 1912]]\n\nShe was the eldest of the eight siblings. Her brother [[Virendranath Chattopadhyay]] was a revolutionary, and another brother [[Harindranath Chattopadhyay|Harindranath]] was a poet, a dramatist, and an actor. Their family was well-regarded in Hyderabad, not only for leading the Nizam College of Hyderabad, but also as Hyderabad's most famous artists in a time of British rule. Being an artist in the era of British rule in India was considered a risky career, yet with their progressive values, they pursued them anyway.<ref name=\"PoemHunter\">{{cite web |title=Biography of Sarojini Naidu |url=http://www.poemhunter.com/sarojini-naidu/biography/ |website=PoemHunter.Com |accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nSarojini Naidu, having passed her matriculation examination from the [[University of Madras]], took a four-year break from her studies. In 1895, [[H.E.H. the Nizam's Charitable Trust]] founded by the 6th [[Nizam]], [[Mir Mahbub Ali Khan|Mahbub Ali Khan]] who gave her the chance to study in England, first at [[King's College London|King's College, London]] and later at [[Girton College, Cambridge]].\n\nSarojini met Paidipati Govindarajulu Naidu, a physician, and at the age of 19, after finishing her studies, she married him. At that time, [[Inter-caste marriage]]s were not as common as they are today, but both their families approved their marriage. In addition, at that time, inter-regional marriage was also uncommon and looked down upon. As Sarojini was from Bengal, while Paidipati Naidu was from Andhra Pradesh, this was an inter-regional marriage of East and South India, with two opposing cultures.<ref name=\"PoemHunter\" /> The couple had five children. Their daughter [[Padmaja Naidu|Paidipati Padmaja]] also joined the independence movement and was part of the [[Quit India Movement]]. She was appointed the Governor of the State of [[Uttar Pradesh]] soon after Indian independence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Padmaja Naidu Dies at 75; ExWest Bengal Governor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/05/03/archives/padmaja-naidu-dies-at-75-exwest-bengal-governor.html|accessdate=19 February 2018|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=3 May 1975}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Early work===\n[[File:Mahatma & Sarojini Naidu 1930.JPG|thumb|Sarojini Naidu (extreme right) with [[Mahatma Gandhi]] during [[Salt Satyagraha]], 1930]]\n\nNaidu joined the [[Indian independence movement]] in the wake of [[Partition of Bengal (1905)|partition of Bengal in 1905]]. She soon met other such leaders as [[Gopal Krishna Gokhale]], [[Rabindranath Tagore]], [[Mahatma Gandhi]] and was inspired to work towards attaining freedom from the colonial regime and social reform.<ref name=\"inc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.inc.in/en/leadership/past-party-president/mrs-sarojini-naidu|title=Mrs. Sarojini Naidu|publisher=[[Indian National Congress]]|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1915 and 1918, Naidu travelled to different regions in India delivering lectures on [[social welfare]], [[women's emancipation|emancipation of women]] and [[nationalism]]. She also helped to establish the [[Women's suffrage#India|Women's Indian Association]] (WIA) in 1917.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pasricha|first=Ashu|title=The political thought of Annie Besant|year=2009|publisher=Concept Pub. Co.|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-8069-585-8|pages=24|url=https://books.google.com/?id=p-j4fWQxpGIC&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=naidu+Women%27s+Indian+Association+%28WIA%29#v=onepage&q=naidu%20Women%27s%20Indian%20Association%20%28WIA%29&f=false}}</ref>\n\nLater in 1917, Naidu also accompanied her colleague [[Annie Besant]], who was the president of [[Home Rule League]] and Women's Indian Association, to present the advocate [[universal suffrage]] in front of the Joint Select Committee in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\nNaidu again went to London in 1919 as a part of the [[All India Home Rule League]] as a part of her continued efforts to advocate for freedom from the British rule. Upon return to India in 1920, she joined Gandhi's [[Satyagraha|Satyagraha Movement]].<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\n===Congress president and increased involvement in the Independence movement===\nNaidu presided over the 1925 Annual Session of the [[Indian National Congress]] at [[Cawnpore]] (now [[Kanpur]]). She was the first Indian woman and second woman overall (after Annie Besant) to do so.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-UjZlNCh-qwC&pg=PA190&dq=naidu+at+indian+national+congress#v=onepage&q=naidu%20at%20indian%20national%20congress&f=false|title=Making India: Colonialism, National Culture, and the Afterlife of Indian English Authority|last=Paranjape|first=Makarand|last2=|first2=|date=2013|publisher=Springer Dordrecht Heidelberg New York japan and Amaryllis, an imprint of Manjul Publishing House Pvt., Ltd., New Delhi|isbn=978-94-007-4660-2|location=New Delhi|pages=190|language=en}}</ref> Naidu said in her address, \"In the battle for liberty, fear is one unforgivable treachery and despair, the one unforgivable sin\".<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\n[[File:Sarojini Naidu plants a tree in Mehrauli, Delhi.jpg|thumb|left|Sarojini Naidu plants a tree in Mehrauli, Delhi.]]\n\nNaidu also presided over East African Indian Congress' 1929 session in South Africa.\n\nNaidu was arrested, along with other Congress leaders including Gandhi, [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], and [[Madan Mohan Malaviya]] for participating in 1930 [[Salt March]]. The Indian National Congress decided to stay away from  the [[First Round Table Conference]] that took place in London owing to the arrests.<ref name=\"inc\" />\n\nIn 1931, however, Naidu and other leaders of the Congress party participated in the [[Second Round Table Conference]] headed by [[Viceroy of India|Viceroy]] [[Lord Irwin]] in the wake of the [[Gandhi-Irwin pact]].<ref name=\"inc\" />\n\nNaidu was one of the major figures to have led the [[Civil Disobedience Movement]] and the [[Quit India Movement]] led by Gandhi. She faced repeated arrests by the British authorities during the time and even spent over 21 months in jail.<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\n===Governor of United Provinces===\nFollowing India's independence from the British rule in 1947, Naidu was appointed as the governor of the [[United Provinces (1937\u201350)|United Provinces]] (present-day [[Uttar Pradesh]]), making her India's first woman governor. She remained in office until her death in March 1949.<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\n==Writing career==\nNaidu began writing at the age of twelve. Her play, ''Maher Muneer'', written in [[Persian language|Persian]] impressed the [[Nawab of Hyderabad]].\n\nIn 1905, her first collection of poems, named ''The Golden Threshold'' was published.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Sarkar, Amar Nath |editor2=Prasad, Bithika|title=Critical response to Indian poetry in English|year=2008|publisher=Sarup & Sons|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-7625-825-8|pages=11|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4NcHdrqUJpYC&pg=PA11&dq=%22The+Broken+Wings%22+was+published+1905+naidu#v=onepage&q=%22The%20Broken%20Wings%22%20was%20published%201905%20naidu&f=false}}</ref> The volume bore an introduction by [[Arthur Symons]]. Her poems were admired by prominent Indian politicians like [[Gopal Krishna Gokhale]].\n\nNaidu poem \"[[In the Bazaars of Hyderabad]]\" was published as a part of ''The Bird of Time'' with her other poems in 1912. \"In the Bazaars of Hyderabad\" was well received by critics, who variously noted Naidu's visceral use of [[Virtual reality|rich sensory images]] in her writing.<ref name=\"Anand and Alurkar\">{{cite book|title=Techniques of counseling guidance, counseling and student personnel in education McGraw-Hill series in education|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=STIF4HvTOBYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|last1=Anand|first1=Renu|last2=Alurkar|first2=Sudha|year=1964|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education|pages=66\u201370|isbn=9780070683815|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Iyer\">{{cite book|title=Musings on Indian Writing in English: Poetry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4D9b4QSeoMIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|first=N Sharada|last=Iyer|year=1964|publisher=Sarup & Sons|pages=150|isbn=9788176255745|accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Jagadisan\">{{cite book|title=A thing of beauty|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7_NShyA_s7YC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|author=Jagadisan|year=2001|publisher=Orient Blackswan|page=55|isbn=9788125016250|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Barot\">{{cite book|title=Perfect Practice Series English Babharati Workbook Std.VIII|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SQQbnmoOTkcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=17\u201320|last=Ashita|first=Barot|publisher= |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n''The Feather of The Dawn'' which contained poems written in 1927 by Naidu was edited and published posthumously in 1961 by her daughter [[Padmaja Naidu]].<ref>{{cite book|title=India in Britain: South Asian Networks and Connections, 1858\u20131950|isbn=978-0-230-39271-7|page=213|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dgYGlJI9vrUC&lpg=PA213&dq=The%20Feather%20of%20The%20Dawn%20Padmaja&pg=PR4#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=13 February 2016|author1=Nasta|first1=Susheila|date=16 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\n[[File:Sarojini Naidu Ashes.jpg|thumb|upright|The ashes of Sarojini Naidu kept at Golden Threshold, Hyderabad before immersion]]\n\nNaidu died of [[cardiac arrest]] at 3:30&nbsp;p.m. ([[Indian Standard Time|IST]]) on 2 March 1949 at the [[Raj Bhavan (Uttar Pradesh)|Government House]] in [[Lucknow]]. Upon her return from [[New Delhi]] on 15 February, she was advised rest by her doctors, and all official engagements were cancelled. Her health deteriorated substantially and [[bloodletting]] was performed on the night of 1 March after she complained of severe [[headache]]. She died after collapsing following a fit of cough. Naidu was said to have asked the nurse attending to her to sing to her at about 10:40&nbsp;p.m. (IST) which put her to sleep.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Sarojini Naidu Passes Away|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dQBFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YrcMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3904%2C5941395|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=The Indian Express|date=3 March 1949|page=1}}</ref> The last rites were performed at the [[Gomati River]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Last Rites of Sarojini Naidu at Lucknow|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dgBFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YrcMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1910%2C6038939|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=The Indian Express|date=4 March 1949|page=1}}</ref>\n\nAnalysing her political legacy, English writer and philosopher [[Aldous Huxley]] wrote, \"It has been our good fortune, while in Bombay, to meet Mrs. Sarojini Naidu, the newly elected President of the All-India Congress and a woman who combines in the most remarkable way great intellectual power with charm, sweetness with courageous energy, a wide culture with originality, and earnestness with humour. If all Indian politicians are like Mrs. Naidu, then the country is fortunate indeed.\"<ref>Huxley, Aldous (1926). ''Jesting Pilate: Travels Through India, Burma, Malaya, Japan, China, and America''. Paragon House, New York. p. 22.</ref>\n\n=== Golden Threshold ===\n{{Main|Golden Threshold}}\n[[File:Golden Threshold in Abids, Hyderabad.JPG|thumbnail|Golden Threshold in 2015]]\nThe Golden Threshold is an off-campus annexe of [[University of Hyderabad]]. The building was the residence of Naidu's father Aghornath Chattopadhyay, the first Principal of Hyderabad College. It was named after Naidu's very first collection of poetry. Golden Threshold now houses Sarojini Naidu School of Arts & Communication of [[University of Hyderabad]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarojini Naidu School of Arts & Communication|url=http://www.uohyd.ac.in/index.php/academics/2011-10-27-18-38-04/sarojini-naidu-school-of-arts-a-communication|accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Chattopadhyay family's residence, it was the centre of many reformist ideas in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], in areas ranging from marriage, education, women's. empowerment, literature and nationalism. Specifically, the reformist ideas included more power for women in a time where politics in India, especially regional politics, was dominated by men. It also included ideas for involvement for women in the arts field. There were also many restrictions on marriage during this time period that persist to this day, such as inter-regional and inter-caste marriages. These ideas were progressive for the era, but brought change in India in slow ways over time.<ref name=\"Sharma2003\">{{cite book|last=Sharma|first=Kaushal Kishore |authorlink=|title=Feminism, Censorship and Other Essays|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QSvfYx4zGB4C&pg=PA56|accessdate=13 February 2014|date=1 January 2003|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-7625-373-4|pages=56\u201357|chapter=Sarojini Naidu: A Preface to Her Poetry}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*1905: ''The Golden Threshold'', published in the United Kingdom<ref name=20cile>Knippling, Alpana Sharma, \"Chapter 3: Twentieth-Century Indian Literature in English\", in Natarajan, Nalini, and Emanuel Sampath Nelson, editors, [https://books.google.com/books?id=1lTnv6o-d_oC&dq=Urdu+poets&num=100&output=html ''Handbook of Twentieth-century Literatures of India''] (Google books link), Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Publishing Group, 1996, {{ISBN|978-0-313-28778-7}}, retrieved 10 December 2008</ref> (text [https://archive.org/details/goldenthreshold00naidgoog available online])\n*1912: ''The Bird of Time: Songs of Life, Death & the Spring'', published in London<ref name=vkg313>Vinayak Krishna Gokak, [https://books.google.com/books?id=WLE8GVsAfEMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Golden Treasury Of Indo-Anglian Poetry (1828\u20131965)'', p 313, New Delhi: Sahitya Akademi (1970, first edition; 2006 reprint)], {{ISBN|81-260-1196-3}}, retrieved 6 August 2010</ref>\n*1917: ''The Broken Wing: Songs of Love, Death and the Spring'', including \"The Gift of India\" (first read in public in 1915)<ref name=vkg313/><ref>Sisir Kumar Das, [https://books.google.com/books?id=sqBjpV9OzcsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false \"A History of Indian Literature 1911\u20131956: Struggle for Freedom: Triumph and Tragedy\"], p 523, New Delhi: Sahitya Akademi (1995), {{ISBN|81-7201-798-7}}; retrieved 10 August 2010</ref>\n*1919: ''Muhammad Jinnah: An Ambassador of Unity''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fline/fl2216/stories/20050812001308300.htm |title=Jinnah in India's history |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=12 August 2001 |accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n*1943: ''The Sceptred Flute: Songs of India'', Allahabad: Kitabistan, posthumously published<ref name=vkg313/>\n*1961: ''The Feather of the Dawn'', posthumously published, edited by her daughter, [[Padmaja Naidu]]<ref>Lal, P., ''Modern Indian Poetry in English: An Anthology & a Credo'', p 362, Calcutta: Writers Workshop, second edition, 1971 (however, on page 597 an \"editor's note\" states contents \"on the following pages are a supplement to the first edition\" and is dated \"1972\")</ref>\n*1971:''The Indian Weavers''<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian Weavers|url=http://www.poemhunter.com/poem/indian-weavers/|publisher=Poem Hunter|accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nNaidu was awarded the [[Kaisar-i-Hind Medal]] by the British government for her work during the plague epidemic in India, but she later returned it as a form of protest against the April 1919 [[Jallianwala Bagh massacre]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Jain|first=Reena|title=Sarojini Naidu|url=http://www.streeshakti.com/bookS.aspx?author=10|publisher=Stree Shakti|accessdate=25 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nFor her work in the field of poetry writing, Naidu was given the title of \"Nightingale of India\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/children/nightingale-of-india/article19093162.ece|title=Nightingale of India|date=17 June 2017|website=[[The Hindu]]|first=Seline|last=Augestine|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Google India commemorated Naidu's 135th birth anniversary with a [[Google Doodle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Doodle celebrates Sarojini Naidu's 135th Birthday|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/02/google-doodle-celebrates-sarojini-naidus-135th-birthday/|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref> Naidu was listed  among \"150 Leading Women\" list by the [[University of London]] to mark the 150 years since women gained access to higher education in the United Kingdom in 2018.<ref>[https://london.ac.uk/about-us/leading-women-1868-2018/ \"Leading Women 1868\u20132018\"], University of London.</ref>\n\nAsteroid [[5647 Sarojininaidu]], discovered by [[Eleanor Helin]] at [[Palomar Observatory]] in 1990, was named in her memory.<ref name=\"jpldata\" /> The official {{MoMP|5647|naming citation}} was published by the [[Minor Planet Center]] on 27 August 2019 ({{small|[[Minor Planet Circulars|M.P.C.]] 115893}}).<ref name=\"MPC-Circulars-Archive\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry|Biography}}\n* [[Indian English literature]]\n* [[Indian literature]]\n* [[Indian poetry]]\n* [[Indian poetry in English]]\n* [[List of Indian poets]]\n* [[List of Indian writers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"jpldata\">{{cite web\n  |type       = 11 May 2019 last obs.\n  |title      = JPL Small-Body Database Browser: 5647 Sarojininaidu (1990 TZ)\n  |url        = https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2005647\n  |publisher  = [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n  |accessdate = 25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-Circulars-Archive\">{{cite web\n  |title      = MPC/MPO/MPS Archive\n  |work       = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/ECS/MPCArchive/MPCArchive_TBL.html\n  |accessdate = 25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooksby=yes|viaf= 20485679}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Gupta|first1=Indra|title=India's 50 most illustrious women|date=2004|location=New Delhi |publisher=Icon Publications|edition=2nd}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Baig|first1=Tara Ali|title=Sarojini Naidu: portrait of a patriot|date=1985|location=New Delhi |publisher=Congress Centenary (1985) Celebrations Committee, AICC (I)}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Ramachandran Nair|first1=K. R.|title=Three Indo-Anglian poets: Henry Derozio, Toru Dutt, and Sarojini Naidu|date=1987 |location=New Delhi |publisher=Sterling Publishers}}\n* {{cite book|author=Padmini Sengupta|title=Sarojini Naido |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ikVKnQEACAAJ|year=1997|publisher=}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n{{commons category|Sarojini Naidu}}\n* [https://www.academia.edu/4132256/International_Journal_of_English_and_Literature_IJEL_ The poetry of Sarojini Naidu: A fusion of English language and Indian culture]\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Naidu,+Sarojini | name=Sarojini Naidu}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Sarojini Naidu}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=3569}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080518090448/http://www.poetseers.org/the_great_poets/in/sarojini_naidu/ Biography and Poems of Sarojini Naidu ]\n* [http://www.rediff.com/freedom/19let1.htm Letter written by Sarojini Naidu ]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=h6v8HsRUBucC&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=Bazaars+of+hyderabad,+sarojini+naidu&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7#v=twopage&q=nizam%20college&f=false Sarojini Naidu: An introduction to her life, work, and poetry By Vishwanath S. Naravane]\n* [http://www.saadigitalarchive.org/entity/sarojini-naidu Sarojini Naidu materials at the South Asian American Digital Archive (SAADA)]\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/022371}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress Presidents}}\n{{Indian independence movement}}\n{{Governors of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naidu, Sarojini}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian women politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Bengali poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Bengali female poets]]\n[[Category:Brahmos]]\n[[Category:English-language poets from India]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Telangana]]\n[[Category:Indian tax resisters]]\n[[Category:Indian women poets]]\n[[Category:People from Bikrampur]]\n[[Category:People from Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Indian National Congress]]\n[[Category:Women in Telangana politics]]\n[[Category:Women in Uttar Pradesh politics]]\n[[Category:Women Indian independence activists]]\n[[Category:Women state governors of India]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Telangana]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|20th-century Indian political activist and poet}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| order        = 1st\n| office       = Governor of United Provinces\n\n| term_start = 15 August 1947\n| term_end     = 2 March 1949\n| predecessor  = Position established\n| successor    = [[Hormasji Peroshaw Mody]]\n| office2      = [[President of the Indian National Congress]]\n|term2=1925-1926\n| predecessor2 = [[Mahatma Gandhi]]\n| successor2   = [[S. Srinivasa Iyengar]]\n| name         = Sarojini Naidu\n| image        = Sarojini Naidu 1964 stamp of India.jpg\n| caption      = Naidu on a 1964 stamp of India\n| birth_name   = Sarojini Chatterjee\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1879|2|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Hyderabad]], [[Hyderabad State]], [[British India]] (now in [[Telangana]], [[India]])\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1949|3|2|1879|2|13|df=yes}}\n| death_place  = [[Lucknow]], [[United Provinces (1937\u20131950)|United Provinces]], [[Dominion of India|India]]\n| nationality  = Indian\n| alma_mater   = [[University of Madras]]<br />[[King's College London]]<br />[[Girton College, Cambridge]]\n| occupation   = Political activist, poet-writer\n| party        = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| spouse       = Govindarajulu Naidu (1898\u20131949)\n| children     = 5; including [[Padmaja Naidu|Padmaja]]\n| relatives    = [[Harindranatha Chattopadhyay]], [[Virendranath Chattopadhyay]], [[Suhasini Chattopadhyay]], [[Leela Naidu]]\n| module       = {{Infobox writer\n| embed        = yes\n| language     = [[English language|English]]\n| genre        =\n| notableworks = [[Golden Threshold]]; [[In the Bazaars of Hyderabad]]\n| subject = [[Indian nationalism]]\n| signature = Sarojini Naidu signature.png\n}}\n}}\n'''Sarojini Naidu''' (n\u00e9e '''Chattopadhyay'''; 13 February 1879 \u2013 2 March 1949) was an Indian political activist and poet. A proponent of [[civil rights]], [[women's emancipation]], and [[anti-imperialistic]] ideas, she was an important figure in [[Indian independence movement|India's struggle for independence from colonial rule]]. Naidu's work as a poet earned her the sobriquet '''Nightingale of India'''.\n\nBorn in a [[Bengalis|Bengali]] family in [[Hyderabad]], Naidu was educated in [[Chennai]], [[London]] and [[Cambridge]]. Following her time in England, where she worked as a [[suffragist]], she was drawn to [[Indian National Congress]]' movement for India's independence from British rule. She became a part of the Indian nationalist movement and became a follower of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] and his idea of [[swaraj]]. She was appointed the President of the Indian National Congress in 1925 and later became the Governor of the [[United Provinces (1937\u201350)|United Provinces]] in 1947, becoming the first woman to hold the office of Governor in the [[Dominion of India]].\n\nNaidu's poetry includes both children's poems and others written on more serious themes including patriotism, romance, and tragedy. Published in 1912, \"[[In the Bazaars of Hyderabad]]\" remains one of her most popular poems. She was married to Govindarajulu Naidu, a [[general physician]] and had five children with him. She died of a [[cardiac arrest]] on 2 March 1949.\n\n==Education ==\nSarojini Naidu was born in [[Hyderabad]] to Aghorenath Chattopadhyay, a [[Bengali Brahmin]] who was the principal of the Nizam's College in Hyderabad. Her parental home was at Brahmangaon in [[Bikrampur]] (in present-day [[Bangladesh]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Naidu,_Sarojini|title=Naidu, Sarojini|accessdate=5 August 2015|publisher=[[Banglapedia]]: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh|author=Lilyma Ahmed}}</ref> Her father, Aghorenath Chattopadhyay, with a doctorate of Science from [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh University]], settled in Hyderabad, where he administered Hyderabad college, which later became [[Nizam College]] in Hyderabad. Her mother, Barada Sundari Devi Chattopadhyay, was a poet and used to write poetry in Bengali.\n\n[[File:Sarojini Naidu.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Sarojini Naidu in 1912]]\n\nShe was the eldest of the eight siblings. Her brother [[Virendranath Chattopadhyay]] was a revolutionary, and another brother [[Harindranath Chattopadhyay|Harindranath]] was a poet, a dramatist, and an actor. Their family was well-regarded in Hyderabad, not only for leading the Nizam College of Hyderabad, but also as Hyderabad's most famous artists in a time of British rule. Being an artist in the era of British rule in India was considered a risky career, yet with their progressive values, they pursued them anyway.<ref name=\"PoemHunter\">{{cite web |title=Biography of Sarojini Naidu |url=http://www.poemhunter.com/sarojini-naidu/biography/ |website=PoemHunter.Com |accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nSarojini Naidu, having passed her matriculation examination from the [[University of Madras]], took a four-year break from her studies. In 1895, [[H.E.H. the Nizam's Charitable Trust]] founded by the 6th [[Nizam]], [[Mir Mahbub Ali Khan|Mahbub Ali Khan]] who gave her the chance to study in England, first at [[King's College London|King's College, London]] and later at [[Girton College, Cambridge]].\n\nSarojini met Paidipati Govindarajulu Naidu, a physician, and at the age of 19, after finishing her studies, she married him. At that time, [[Inter-caste marriage]]s were not as common as they are today, but both their families approved their marriage. In addition, at that time, inter-regional marriage was also uncommon and looked down upon. As Sarojini was from Bengal, while Paidipati Naidu was from Andhra Pradesh, this was an inter-regional marriage of East and South India, with two opposing cultures.<ref name=\"PoemHunter\" /> The couple had five children. Their daughter [[Padmaja Naidu|Paidipati Padmaja]] also joined the independence movement and was part of the [[Quit India Movement]]. She was appointed the Governor of the State of [[Uttar Pradesh]] soon after Indian independence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Padmaja Naidu Dies at 75; ExWest Bengal Governor|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/05/03/archives/padmaja-naidu-dies-at-75-exwest-bengal-governor.html|accessdate=19 February 2018|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=3 May 1975}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Early work===\n[[File:Mahatma & Sarojini Naidu 1930.JPG|thumb|Sarojini Naidu (extreme right) with [[Mahatma Gandhi]] during [[Salt Satyagraha]], 1930]]\n\nNaidu joined the [[Indian independence movement]] in the wake of [[Partition of Bengal (1905)|partition of Bengal in 1905]]. She soon met other such leaders as [[Gopal Krishna Gokhale]], [[Rabindranath Tagore]], [[Mahatma Gandhi]] and was inspired to work towards attaining freedom from the colonial regime and social reform.<ref name=\"inc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.inc.in/en/leadership/past-party-president/mrs-sarojini-naidu|title=Mrs. Sarojini Naidu|publisher=[[Indian National Congress]]|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1915 and 1918, Naidu travelled to different regions in India delivering lectures on [[social welfare]], [[women's emancipation|emancipation of women]] and [[nationalism]]. She also helped to establish the [[Women's suffrage#India|Women's Indian Association]] (WIA) in 1917.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pasricha|first=Ashu|title=The political thought of Annie Besant|year=2009|publisher=Concept Pub. Co.|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-8069-585-8|pages=24|url=https://books.google.com/?id=p-j4fWQxpGIC&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=naidu+Women%27s+Indian+Association+%28WIA%29#v=onepage&q=naidu%20Women%27s%20Indian%20Association%20%28WIA%29&f=false}}</ref>\n\nLater in 1917, Naidu also accompanied her colleague [[Annie Besant]], who was the president of [[Home Rule League]] and Women's Indian Association, to present the advocate [[universal suffrage]] in front of the Joint Select Committee in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\nNaidu again went to London in 1919 as a part of the [[All India Home Rule League]] as a part of her continued efforts to advocate for freedom from the British rule. Upon return to India in 1920, she joined Gandhi's [[Satyagraha|Satyagraha Movement]].<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\n===Congress president and increased involvement in the Independence movement===\nNaidu presided over the 1925 Annual Session of the [[Indian National Congress]] at [[Cawnpore]] (now [[Kanpur]]). She was the first Indian woman and second woman overall (after Annie Besant) to do so.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-UjZlNCh-qwC&pg=PA190&dq=naidu+at+indian+national+congress#v=onepage&q=naidu%20at%20indian%20national%20congress&f=false|title=Making India: Colonialism, National Culture, and the Afterlife of Indian English Authority|last=Paranjape|first=Makarand|last2=|first2=|date=2013|publisher=Springer Dordrecht Heidelberg New York japan and Amaryllis, an imprint of Manjul Publishing House Pvt., Ltd., New Delhi|isbn=978-94-007-4660-2|location=New Delhi|pages=190|language=en}}</ref> Naidu said in her address, \"In the battle for liberty, fear is one unforgivable treachery and despair, the one unforgivable sin\".<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\n[[File:Sarojini Naidu plants a tree in Mehrauli, Delhi.jpg|thumb|left|Sarojini Naidu plants a tree in Mehrauli, Delhi.]]\n\nNaidu also presided over East African Indian Congress' 1929 session in South Africa.\n\nNaidu was arrested, along with other Congress leaders including Gandhi, [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], and [[Madan Mohan Malaviya]] for participating in 1930 [[Salt March]]. The Indian National Congress decided to stay away from  the [[First Round Table Conference]] that took place in London owing to the arrests.<ref name=\"inc\" />\n\nIn 1931, however, Naidu and other leaders of the Congress party participated in the [[Second Round Table Conference]] headed by [[Viceroy of India|Viceroy]] [[Lord Irwin]] in the wake of the [[Gandhi-Irwin pact]].<ref name=\"inc\" />\n\nNaidu was one of the major figures to have led the [[Civil Disobedience Movement]] and the [[Quit India Movement]] led by Gandhi. She faced repeated arrests by the British authorities during the time and even spent over 21 months in jail.<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\n===Governor of United Provinces===\nFollowing India's independence from the British rule in 1947, Naidu was appointed as the governor of the [[United Provinces (1937\u201350)|United Provinces]] (present-day [[Uttar Pradesh]]), making her India's first woman governor. She remained in office until her death in March 1949.<ref name=\"inc\"/>\n\n==Writing career==\nNaidu began writing at the age of twelve. Her play, ''Maher Muneer'', written in [[Persian language|Persian]] impressed the [[Nawab of Hyderabad]].\n\nIn 1905, her first collection of poems, named ''The Golden Threshold'' was published.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Sarkar, Amar Nath |editor2=Prasad, Bithika|title=Critical response to Indian poetry in English|year=2008|publisher=Sarup & Sons|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-7625-825-8|pages=11|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4NcHdrqUJpYC&pg=PA11&dq=%22The+Broken+Wings%22+was+published+1905+naidu#v=onepage&q=%22The%20Broken%20Wings%22%20was%20published%201905%20naidu&f=false}}</ref> The volume bore an introduction by [[Arthur Symons]]. Her poems were admired by prominent Indian politicians like [[Gopal Krishna Gokhale]].\n\nNaidu poem \"[[In the Bazaars of Hyderabad]]\" was published as a part of ''The Bird of Time'' with her other poems in 1912. \"In the Bazaars of Hyderabad\" was well received by critics, who variously noted Naidu's visceral use of [[Virtual reality|rich sensory images]] in her writing.<ref name=\"Anand and Alurkar\">{{cite book|title=Techniques of counseling guidance, counseling and student personnel in education McGraw-Hill series in education|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=STIF4HvTOBYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|last1=Anand|first1=Renu|last2=Alurkar|first2=Sudha|year=1964|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education|pages=66\u201370|isbn=9780070683815|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Iyer\">{{cite book|title=Musings on Indian Writing in English: Poetry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4D9b4QSeoMIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|first=N Sharada|last=Iyer|year=1964|publisher=Sarup & Sons|pages=150|isbn=9788176255745|accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Jagadisan\">{{cite book|title=A thing of beauty|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7_NShyA_s7YC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|author=Jagadisan|year=2001|publisher=Orient Blackswan|page=55|isbn=9788125016250|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Barot\">{{cite book|title=Perfect Practice Series English Babharati Workbook Std.VIII|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SQQbnmoOTkcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=17\u201320|last=Ashita|first=Barot|publisher= |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n''The Feather of The Dawn'' which contained poems written in 1927 by Naidu was edited and published posthumously in 1961 by her daughter [[Padmaja Naidu]].<ref>{{cite book|title=India in Britain: South Asian Networks and Connections, 1858\u20131950|isbn=978-0-230-39271-7|page=213|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dgYGlJI9vrUC&lpg=PA213&dq=The%20Feather%20of%20The%20Dawn%20Padmaja&pg=PR4#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=13 February 2016|author1=Nasta|first1=Susheila|date=16 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\n[[File:Sarojini Naidu Ashes.jpg|thumb|upright|The ashes of Sarojini Naidu kept at Golden Threshold, Hyderabad before immersion]]\n\nNaidu died of [[cardiac arrest]] at 3:30&nbsp;p.m. ([[Indian Standard Time|IST]]) on 2 March 1949 at the [[Raj Bhavan (Uttar Pradesh)|Government House]] in [[Lucknow]]. Upon her return from [[New Delhi]] on 15 February, she was advised rest by her doctors, and all official engagements were cancelled. Her health deteriorated substantially and [[bloodletting]] was performed on the night of 1 March after she complained of severe [[headache]]. She died after collapsing following a fit of cough. Naidu was said to have asked the nurse attending to her to sing to her at about 10:40&nbsp;p.m. (IST) which put her to sleep.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Sarojini Naidu Passes Away|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dQBFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YrcMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3904%2C5941395|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=The Indian Express|date=3 March 1949|page=1}}</ref> The last rites were performed at the [[Gomati River]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Last Rites of Sarojini Naidu at Lucknow|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dgBFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YrcMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1910%2C6038939|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=The Indian Express|date=4 March 1949|page=1}}</ref>\n\nAnalysing her political legacy, English writer and philosopher [[Aldous Huxley]] wrote, \"It has been our good fortune, while in Bombay, to meet Mrs. Sarojini Naidu, the newly elected President of the All-India Congress and a woman who combines in the most remarkable way great intellectual power with charm, sweetness with courageous energy, a wide culture with originality, and earnestness with humour. If all Indian politicians are like Mrs. Naidu, then the country is fortunate indeed.\"<ref>Huxley, Aldous (1926). ''Jesting Pilate: Travels Through India, Burma, Malaya, Japan, China, and America''. Paragon House, New York. p. 22.</ref>\n\n=== Golden Threshold ===\n{{Main|Golden Threshold}}\n[[File:Golden Threshold in Abids, Hyderabad.JPG|thumbnail|Golden Threshold in 2015]]\nThe Golden Threshold is an off-campus annexe of [[University of Hyderabad]]. The building was the residence of Naidu's father Aghornath Chattopadhyay, the first Principal of Hyderabad College. It was named after Naidu's very first collection of poetry. Golden Threshold now houses Sarojini Naidu School of Arts & Communication of [[University of Hyderabad]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarojini Naidu School of Arts & Communication|url=http://www.uohyd.ac.in/index.php/academics/2011-10-27-18-38-04/sarojini-naidu-school-of-arts-a-communication|accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Chattopadhyay family's residence, it was the centre of many reformist ideas in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], in areas ranging from marriage, education, women's. empowerment, literature and nationalism. Specifically, the reformist ideas included more power for women in a time where politics in India, especially regional politics, was dominated by men. It also included ideas for involvement for women in the arts field. There were also many restrictions on marriage during this time period that persist to this day, such as inter-regional and inter-caste marriages. These ideas were progressive for the era, but brought change in India in slow ways over time.<ref name=\"Sharma2003\">{{cite book|last=Sharma|first=Kaushal Kishore |authorlink=|title=Feminism, Censorship and Other Essays|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QSvfYx4zGB4C&pg=PA56|accessdate=13 February 2014|date=1 January 2003|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-7625-373-4|pages=56\u201357|chapter=Sarojini Naidu: A Preface to Her Poetry}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*1905: ''The Golden Threshold'', published in the United Kingdom<ref name=20cile>Knippling, Alpana Sharma, \"Chapter 3: Twentieth-Century Indian Literature in English\", in Natarajan, Nalini, and Emanuel Sampath Nelson, editors, [https://books.google.com/books?id=1lTnv6o-d_oC&dq=Urdu+poets&num=100&output=html ''Handbook of Twentieth-century Literatures of India''] (Google books link), Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Publishing Group, 1996, {{ISBN|978-0-313-28778-7}}, retrieved 10 December 2008</ref> (text [https://archive.org/details/goldenthreshold00naidgoog available online])\n*1912: ''The Bird of Time: Songs of Life, Death & the Spring'', published in London<ref name=vkg313>Vinayak Krishna Gokak, [https://books.google.com/books?id=WLE8GVsAfEMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Golden Treasury Of Indo-Anglian Poetry (1828\u20131965)'', p 313, New Delhi: Sahitya Akademi (1970, first edition; 2006 reprint)], {{ISBN|81-260-1196-3}}, retrieved 6 August 2010</ref>\n*1917: ''The Broken Wing: Songs of Love, Death and the Spring'', including \"The Gift of India\" (first read in public in 1915)<ref name=vkg313/><ref>Sisir Kumar Das, [https://books.google.com/books?id=sqBjpV9OzcsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false \"A History of Indian Literature 1911\u20131956: Struggle for Freedom: Triumph and Tragedy\"], p 523, New Delhi: Sahitya Akademi (1995), {{ISBN|81-7201-798-7}}; retrieved 10 August 2010</ref>\n*1919: ''Muhammad Jinnah: An Ambassador of Unity''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fline/fl2216/stories/20050812001308300.htm |title=Jinnah in India's history |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=12 August 2001 |accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n*1943: ''The Sceptred Flute: Songs of India'', Allahabad: Kitabistan, posthumously published<ref name=vkg313/>\n*1961: ''The Feather of the Dawn'', posthumously published, edited by her daughter, [[Padmaja Naidu]]<ref>Lal, P., ''Modern Indian Poetry in English: An Anthology & a Credo'', p 362, Calcutta: Writers Workshop, second edition, 1971 (however, on page 597 an \"editor's note\" states contents \"on the following pages are a supplement to the first edition\" and is dated \"1972\")</ref>\n*1971:''The Indian Weavers''<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian Weavers|url=http://www.poemhunter.com/poem/indian-weavers/|publisher=Poem Hunter|accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nNaidu was awarded the [[Kaisar-i-Hind Medal]] by the British government for her work during the plague epidemic in India, but she later returned it as a form of protest against the April 1919 [[Jallianwala Bagh massacre]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Jain|first=Reena|title=Sarojini Naidu|url=http://www.streeshakti.com/bookS.aspx?author=10|publisher=Stree Shakti|accessdate=25 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nFor her work in the field of poetry writing, Naidu was given the title of \"Nightingale of India\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/children/nightingale-of-india/article19093162.ece|title=Nightingale of India|date=17 June 2017|website=[[The Hindu]]|first=Seline|last=Augestine|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Google India commemorated Naidu's 135th birth anniversary with a [[Google Doodle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Doodle celebrates Sarojini Naidu's 135th Birthday|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/02/google-doodle-celebrates-sarojini-naidus-135th-birthday/|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref> Naidu was listed  among \"150 Leading Women\" list by the [[University of London]] to mark the 150 years since women gained access to higher education in the United Kingdom in 2018.<ref>[https://london.ac.uk/about-us/leading-women-1868-2018/ \"Leading Women 1868\u20132018\"], University of London.</ref>\n\nAsteroid [[5647 Sarojininaidu]], discovered by [[Eleanor Helin]] at [[Palomar Observatory]] in 1990, was named in her memory.<ref name=\"jpldata\" /> The official {{MoMP|5647|naming citation}} was published by the [[Minor Planet Center]] on 27 August 2019 ({{small|[[Minor Planet Circulars|M.P.C.]] 115893}}).<ref name=\"MPC-Circulars-Archive\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry|Biography}}\n* [[Indian English literature]]\n* [[Indian literature]]\n* [[Indian poetry]]\n* [[Indian poetry in English]]\n* [[List of Indian poets]]\n* [[List of Indian writers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"jpldata\">{{cite web\n  |type       = 11 May 2019 last obs.\n  |title      = JPL Small-Body Database Browser: 5647 Sarojininaidu (1990 TZ)\n  |url        = https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2005647\n  |publisher  = [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n  |accessdate = 25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-Circulars-Archive\">{{cite web\n  |title      = MPC/MPO/MPS Archive\n  |work       = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/ECS/MPCArchive/MPCArchive_TBL.html\n  |accessdate = 25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooksby=yes|viaf= 20485679}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Gupta|first1=Indra|title=India's 50 most illustrious women|date=2004|location=New Delhi |publisher=Icon Publications|edition=2nd}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Baig|first1=Tara Ali|title=Sarojini Naidu: portrait of a patriot|date=1985|location=New Delhi |publisher=Congress Centenary (1985) Celebrations Committee, AICC (I)}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Ramachandran Nair|first1=K. R.|title=Three Indo-Anglian poets: Henry Derozio, Toru Dutt, and Sarojini Naidu|date=1987 |location=New Delhi |publisher=Sterling Publishers}}\n* {{cite book|author=Padmini Sengupta|title=Sarojini Naido |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ikVKnQEACAAJ|year=1997|publisher=}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n{{commons category|Sarojini Naidu}}\n* [https://www.academia.edu/4132256/International_Journal_of_English_and_Literature_IJEL_ The poetry of Sarojini Naidu: A fusion of English language and Indian culture]\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Naidu,+Sarojini | name=Sarojini Naidu}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Sarojini Naidu}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=3569}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080518090448/http://www.poetseers.org/the_great_poets/in/sarojini_naidu/ Biography and Poems of Sarojini Naidu ]\n* [http://www.rediff.com/freedom/19let1.htm Letter written by Sarojini Naidu ]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=h6v8HsRUBucC&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=Bazaars+of+hyderabad,+sarojini+naidu&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7#v=twopage&q=nizam%20college&f=false Sarojini Naidu: An introduction to her life, work, and poetry By Vishwanath S. Naravane]\n* [http://www.saadigitalarchive.org/entity/sarojini-naidu Sarojini Naidu materials at the South Asian American Digital Archive (SAADA)]\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/022371}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress Presidents}}\n{{Indian independence movement}}\n{{Governors of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naidu, Sarojini}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian women politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Bengali poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Bengali female poets]]\n[[Category:Brahmos]]\n[[Category:English-language poets from India]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Telangana]]\n[[Category:Indian tax resisters]]\n[[Category:Indian women poets]]\n[[Category:People from Bikrampur]]\n[[Category:People from Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Indian National Congress]]\n[[Category:Women in Telangana politics]]\n[[Category:Women in Uttar Pradesh politics]]\n[[Category:Women Indian independence activists]]\n[[Category:Women state governors of India]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Telangana]]\n", "name_user": "103.216.214.236", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEducation)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarojini_Naidu"}
{"title_page": "Numan Kurtulmu\u015f", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Numan Kurtulmu\u015f\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Numan Kurtulmu\u015f Foto Bal\u0131kesir.jpg\n| imagesize = 220px\n| nationality = Turkish\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1959|3|23}}\n| birth_place = [[\u00dcnye]], Ordu Province, Turkey\n| spouse = Sevgi Kurtulmu\u015f\n| alma_mater = [[Istanbul University]]\n| party = [[Virtue Party|FP]]<br /> [[Felicity Party|SP]]<br /> [[People's Voice Party|HAS Party]]<br />[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n| office = Deputy chair of [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n| term_start = 18 August 2018\n| term_end =\n| president = [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]\n| predecessor = [[Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m]]\n| successor =\n| order1 = [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Culture and Tourism]]\n| term_start1 = 19 July 2017\n| term_end1 = 10 July 2018\n| 1blankname1 =\n| 1namedata1 =\n| primeminister1 = [[Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Nabi Avc\u0131]]\n| successor1 = [[Mehmet Nuri Ersoy]]\n| order2 = [[Deputy Prime Minister of Turkey]]\n| term_start2 = 24 May 2016\n| term_end2 = 19 July 2017\n| 1blankname2 =\n| 1namedata2 = \n| primeminister2 = [[Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Numan Kurtulmu\u015f]]\n| successor2 = [[Bekir Bozda\u011f]]\n| order3 = [[Deputy Prime Minister of Turkey]]\n| term_start3 = 24 May 2016\n| term_end3 = 19 July 2017\n| 1blankname3 =\n| 1namedata3 = \n| primeminister3 = [[Ahmet Davuto\u011flu]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Emrullah \u0130\u015fler]]\n| successor3 = [[Numan Kurtulmu\u015f]]\n| order4 = [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey#Composition|Member of the Grand National Assembly]]\n| term_start4 = 8 July 2018\n| term_end4 = \n| constituency4 = [[\u0130stanbul (electoral districts)|\u0130stanbul]] [[\u0130stanbul (3rd electoral district)|(III)]] ([[2018 Turkish general election|2018]])\n| term_start5 = 7 June 2015\n| term_end5 = 24 June 2018\n| constituency5 = [[Ordu (electoral district)|Ordu]] ([[June 2015 Turkish general election|June 2015]], [[November 2015 Turkish general election|Nov 2015]])\n| order6 = [[People's Voice Party|Leader of the People's Voice Party]]\n| term_start6 = 1 November 2010\n| term_end6 = 19 September 2012\n| predecessor6 = ''Position established''\n| successor6 = ''Position abolished''\n| order7 = [[Felicity Party|Leader of the Felicity Party]]\n| term_start7 = 26 October 2008\n| term_end7 = 17 October 2010\n| predecessor7 = [[Recai Kutan]]\n| successor7 = [[Necmettin Erbakan]]\n| signature = \n| website = [http://www.numankurtulmus.com.tr/ numankurtulmus.com.tr/]\n| cabinet = [[First Davuto\u011flu Cabinet|62nd]], [[2015 interim election government of Turkey|63rd]], [[Third Davuto\u011flu Cabinet|64th]], [[Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m Cabinet|65th]]\n}}\n'''Numan Kurtulmu\u015f''' (born 23 March 1959) is a Turkish politician and [[academician]]. [[Deputy chairman]] of [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]].\n\nHe served as [[Deputy Prime Minister of Turkey]] in the 62. 63. 64. 65. [[AK Party]] governments between 2014 and 2017 and [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Culture and Tourism]] between 2017 and 2018. Previously he served as the leader of [[Felicity Party]] between 2008 and 2010 and [[People's Voice Party]] between 2010 and 2012.\n\n== Personal life ==\n=== Family ===\nKurtulmu\u015f was born in [[\u00dcnye]] district of [[Ordu Province]]. He is of [[Georgians in Turkey|Georgian]] descent by his grandmother.<ref name>[http://www.istanbulunyehaber.com/etiket/siyaset//76/ \u0130stanbul \u00dcnye Haber]</ref> His grandfather Numan Kurtulmu\u015f who served as a major in the [[Turkish War of Independence]] on the [[\u00c7anakkale]], [[Erzurum]], [[Batumi]] and [[Azerbaijan]] fronts and fought in the [[Balkans]] and the [[Battle of Sakarya]] then later has injured and retired as a [[veteran]].<ref>[https://www.sabah.com.tr/numan-kurtulmus Biyografi \u2013 Sabah]</ref> He is also the author of Faith Commentary, known as the first [[Turkish language|Turkish]] religious guide which written by the [[latin alphabet]].<ref>[https://www.akparti.org.tr/ak-kadro/myk/numan-kurtulmus/ Biyografi \u2013 AK Parti]</ref> His father is Dr. Ismail Niyazi Kurtulmu\u015f. He currently resides in [[Fatih]] district of [[Istanbul]] with his family.\n\nHe married to Sevgi Kurtulmu\u015f in 1988. Children: Ay\u015fe, \u0130smail and Emir. He speaks fluent English. A fan of [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K.|Fenerbah\u00e7e FC]].<ref>[https://www.internethaber.com/numan-kurtulmus Numan Kurtulmu\u015f \u2013 \u0130nternethaber]</ref>\n\n=== Education and Academic career ===\nHe studied at Istanbul Imam Hatip High School, [[bachelor]] in 1982 and [[master degree]] in 1984 at [[Istanbul University]] Faculty of Business Administration.\n\nHe had been United States of America to the postgraduate studies at [[Temple University]] School of Business & Management in 1988\u20131989.\n\nHe was also a [[visiting researcher]] at [[Cornell University]] New York State School of Industrial & Labor Relations between 1990 and 1993. He got a PhD title from [[Istanbul University]] in 1992. Became an [[associate professor]] in 1994 and promoted to [[professorship]] in 2004 at [[Istanbul University]] [[Faculty of Economics]].<ref>[http://www.milliyet.com.tr/Siyaset/SonDakika.aspx?aType=SonDakika&Kategori=siyaset&KategoriID=&ArticleID=1005416&Date=20.10.2008&b=Erdogana%20entelektuel%20rakip Tayyip Erdo\u011fan\u2019a entelekt\u00fcel rakip \u2013 Milliyet Gazetesi]</ref> He was the [[assistant]] of [[Sabahattin Zaim]], who known as a 'the great professor'.<ref>[https://www.iyv.org.tr/tr/haberler/36/sabahattin-zaim-anma-gecesi.html Sabahattin Zaim Gecesi \u2013 \u0130YC]</ref>\n\nHe taught politics, [[labor economics]] and [[human resources management]] at [[Istanbul University]] Faculty of Economics and economics and [[political communication]] at [[Istanbul Commerce University]]. He also participated as a speaker in symposiums and seminars.\n\n=== Books ===\nHe's authored two books \"Post-Industrial Transformation\" and \"The Japanese Human Resource Management\".  Published master's degree and Phd thesis on 'Integration of Inventory Management by the Database Approach' and 'The change of Industrial Relations for Terms of Model Human Type', also with many articles.\n\n== Political career ==\n[[File:High-level Meeting of the Ministers of Tourism of the EU member states \"Tourism and economic growth\" Handshake (38428157830).jpg|thumb|Numan Kurtulmu\u015f meets Minister of Tourism of Bulgaria [[Nikolina Angelkova]], 2018]]\nHe was kicked-off politic on [[Virtue Party]] in 1998. The party has been shutted down by [[Constitutional Court]] and he joined [[Felicity Party]]. Elected as chairman at the [[party congress]] held in 2008 and has been here until 2010.  Leaded establishing the [[People's Voice Party]] (HAS Party) in 2010. Upon the proposal of [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]] and [[People's Voice Party|HAS Party]] united in 2012. Within the framework of this combination, HAS Party has been terminated itself and Kurtulmu\u015f joined AK Party with many people.\n\n=== Virtue Party (1998\u20132001) ===\nIn 1998, he began the political career with [[Necmettin Erbakan]] and served as the chairman in [[Istanbul]] and a Member of the Main Administrative Board. When ended [[Virtue Party]], he joined the [[Felicity Party]] in 2001.\n\n=== Felicity Party (2001\u20132010) ===\nHe served as chairman in Istanbul and Deputy Chairman of Party until 2008 at [[Felicity Party]]. [[Recai Kutan]] who Chairman of Felicity Party announced on 17 October 2008 that Numan Kurtulmu\u015f will be [[candidate]] in the party congress to be held in Ankara on 26 October 2008.<ref>[http://www.internethaber.com/news_detail.php?id=161580 \u0130\u015fte Saadet'in yeni lideri \u2013 \u0130nternet Haber]</ref><ref>[http://www.haber7.com/haber/20081016/Saadet-Partisi-son-kararini-verdi.php Saadet Partisi, son karar\u0131n\u0131 verdi! \u2013 Haber 7]</ref><ref>[http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/10076179.asp?gid=233&sz=51524 Saadet Partisi\u2019nde Kurtulmu\u015f d\u00f6nemi \u2013 H\u00fcrriyet Gazetesi]</ref> The slogan was \"Felicity Now!\" And he was elected as a Chairman of [[Felicity Party]] by all valid 924 vote of the used 946 at 3rd Party Congress held in Ankara Atat\u00fcrk Sports Hall.<ref>[http://www.milligazete.com.tr/haber/sahit-olun-tarih-yaziliyor-82499.htm \u015eahit olun!.. tarih yaz\u0131l\u0131yor \u2013 Milli Gazete]</ref><ref>[http://haber.gazetevatan.com/haberdetay.asp?detay=Kutan_veda_etti_205610_9&tarih=27.10.2008&Newsid=205610&Categoryid=9  Kutan veda etti \u2013 Vatan Gazetesi]</ref><ref>[http://yenisafak.com.tr/Politika/?t=27.10.2008&i=146965 Kurtulmu\u015f'tan vira Bismillah \u2013 Yeni \u015eafak Gazetesi]</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he had divergency with Necmettin Erbakan who the leader of the Milli G\u00f6r\u00fc\u015f Movement. Numan Kurtulmu\u015f was re-elected as Chairman of Party, participating as just one candidate of the two lists at the 4th Party Congress held in Ankara on 11 July 2010. Numan Kurtulmu\u015f was participated the Election of Main Administrative Board with the white list against Necmettin Erbakan's green list. And the winner white list meant to be kicking Necmettin Erbakan and his friends out.<ref>[https://www.milliyet.com.tr/siyaset/saadet-iki-parca-1262780 Saadet iki par\u00e7a \u2013 Milliyet]</ref>\n\nAnd then later 650 delegates asked congress again, but this request was rejected by Party's General Administrative Board. Upon the decision appointment of the congress call committee by the court, 53 chairman, 65 mayors and many politician left Felicity Party on 1 October 2010.<ref>[http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/n.php?n=turkish-conservative-party-leader-resigns-2010-10-01 H\u00fcrriyet Daily News \u2013 Felicity Party]</ref>\n\nKurtulmu\u015f announced a new political movement, calls Civilization Politics Movement.<ref name=star>[http://www.stargazete.com/politika/adini-koydu-medeniyet-siyaseti-haber-299445.htm Ad\u0131n\u0131 koydu: Medeniyet siyaseti \u2013 Star]</ref>\n\n=== People's Voice Party (2010\u20132012) ===\n[[File:Numan Kurtulmu\u015f \u0130smail Heniye.jpeg|thumb|Numan Kurtulmu\u015f meets Prime Minister of Palestine [[Ismail Haniyeh]], 2012]]\n235 politician who united around Civilization Politics Movement announced that founded the [[People's Voice Party]] (HAS Party) on 1 November 2010.<ref>[http://www.cnnturk.com/2010/turkiye/10/31/kurtulmusun.partisi.hazir.halkin.sesi/594861.0/ Kurtulmu\u015f'un partisi haz\u0131r: \"Halk\u0131n Sesi\" \u2013 CNN T\u00fcrk]</ref> And Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as Chairman of Party by the 207 vote of 210 delegates<ref>[https://www.haberturk.com/gundem/haber/575684-has-parti-1-olagan-kongresi HAS Parti 1. Ola\u011fan Kongresi \u2013 Habert\u00fcrk]</ref> at the 1st Party Congress held in Ankara Atat\u00fcrk Sports Hall on 28 November 2010 on the 28th day of the founded of HAS Party.<ref>[http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/n.php?n=has-party-halted-its-first-convention-2010-11-28 H\u00fcrriyet Daily News \u2013 People's Voice Party]</ref>\n\n==== Combination process ====\nChairman of [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]] and Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] offered Kurtulmu\u015f to combinate AK Party with HAS Party on 12 July 2012.<ref>[http://yenisafak.com.tr/Politika/?t=12.07.2012&c=2&i=394245&k=f2 Ba\u015fbakan Erdo\u011fan resmen teklif etti \u2013 Yeni \u015eafak]</ref> According to the decision taken by the authorized persons of two sides and combination process has started.<ref>[http://siyaset.milliyet.com.tr/suleyman-soylu-da-ak-partide/siyaset/siyasetdetay/15.08.2012/1581241/default.htm S\u00fcleyman Soylu da AK Parti'de \u2013 Milliyet]</ref> HAS Party invited the delegates and dissolved itself at the extraordinary congress held in 19 September 2012 by 165 votes of the current 177 delegates according to the decision of combination.<ref>[http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/hsp-dissolves-itself-as-its-leader-plans-to-join-the-ruling-party.aspx?pageID=238&nID=30540&NewsCatID=33 H\u00fcrriyet Daily News \u2013 HAS Party Dissolves]</ref>\n\n=== Justice and Development Party (2012\u2013Current) ===\nAfter the HAS Party's termination, Kurtulmu\u015f joined [[AK Party]] at a ceremony held in [[\u0130stanbul]] on 22 September 2012 with many people.<ref>[http://www.haberturk.com/gundem/haber/778770-erdogan-yuvaniza-hos-geldiniz Numan Kurtulmu\u015f resmen AK Parti'li \u2013 Habert\u00fcrk]</ref> \n\n\u2013 Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as a Member of Main Administrative Board at 4th [[AK Party]] Congress held in Ankara on 30 September 2012, was appointed as vice chairman of party on the economy politics.<ref>[http://www.haber7.com/ic-politika/haber/936265-ak-partide-yeni-yonetim-kadrosu AK Parti'de yeni y\u00f6netim kadrosu \u2013 Haber7]</ref>\n\n\u2013 When Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] was elected as [[President of Turkey]] at [[presidential elections]] in 2014, [[Ahmet Davuto\u011flu]] replaced himself as a Prime Minister and Kurtulmu\u015f became [[Deputy Prime Minister]] at [[First Davuto\u011flu Cabinet|62nd]] Government.<ref>[http://www.haberturk.com/gundem/haber/985009-yeni-kabine-aciklandi Yeni Kabine A\u00e7\u0131kland\u0131 \u2013 Habert\u00fcrk]</ref>\n\n\u2013 Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as the [[Ordu]] [[parliamentarian]] in the elections of June 2015 and became [[Deputy Prime Minister]] and Spokesperson again at the [[2015 interim election government of Turkey|63rd]] Government under Ahmet Davuto\u011flu's Prime Ministry.<ref>[https://www.ntv.com.tr/galeri/turkiye/63-hukumette-yer-alan-isimler,xWMLJkRD7EOtukQkJxOZyw/rnSZm3ePPUyvVA-bVRcpDw 63. H\u00fck\u00fcmet'te yer alacak isimler \u2013 NTV]</ref>\n\n\u2013 Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as the [[Ordu]] parliamentarian again in the elections of November 2015, became [[Deputy Prime Minister]] and Spokesperson again at [[Third Davuto\u011flu Cabinet|64th]] Government under Ahmet Davuto\u011flu's Prime Ministry.<ref>[http://www.ahaber.com.tr/gundem/2015/11/24/numan-kurtulmus-yine-basbakan-yardimcisi Numan Kurtulmu\u015f yine ba\u015fbakan yard\u0131mc\u0131s\u0131 \u2013 aHaber]</ref>\n\n\u2013 Ahmet Davuto\u011flu when resigned prime ministry [[President Erdogan]] gave the government formation duty to [[Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m]]. Kurtulmu\u015f served as deputy prime minister again at [[Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m Cabinet|65th]] Government under Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m's Prime Ministry. After a while held in 19 July 2017 he became [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Culture and Tourism]] in cabinet overhaul.<ref>[https://www.milliyet.com.tr/yerel-haberler/ankara/numan-kurtulmus-kultur-ve-turizm-bakani-oldu-12174905 Numan Kurtulmu\u015f K\u00fclt\u00fcr ve Turizm Bakan\u0131 \u2013 Milliyet]</ref>\n\n\u2013 Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as a parliamentarian of Istanbul on 24 June 2018 and became [[Deputy chairman]] of [[AK Party]] at the 6th AK Party Congress on 18 August 2018.<ref>[https://www.yenisafak.com/gundem/erdoganin-koltugu-kurtulmusa-emanet-3390873 Numan Kurtulmu\u015f Genel Ba\u015fkan Vekili \u2013 Yeni \u015eafak]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://twitter.com/NumanKurtulmus\n\n{{65th government of Turkey}}\n{{64th government of Turkey}}\n{{63rd government of Turkey}}\n{{Cabinet Davuto\u011flu}}\n{{SP Leaders}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kurtulmus, Numan}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from \u00dcnye]]\n[[Category:Turkish people of Georgian descent]]\n[[Category:Virtue Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Felicity Party politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Voice Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Turkish economists]]\n[[Category:Istanbul University alumni]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 25th Parliament of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 63rd government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Istanbul University faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the 26th Parliament of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 64th government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Deputy Prime Ministers of Turkey]]\n\n\n{{Turkey-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Numan Kurtulmu\u015f\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Numan Kurtulmu\u015f Foto Bal\u0131kesir.jpg\n| imagesize = 220px\n| nationality = Turkish\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1959|3|23}}\n| birth_place = [[\u00dcnye]], Ordu Province, Turkey\n| spouse = Sevgi Kurtulmu\u015f\n| alma_mater = [[Istanbul University]]\n| party = [[Virtue Party|FP]]<br /> [[Felicity Party|SP]]<br /> [[People's Voice Party|HAS Party]]<br />[[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n| office = Deputy chair of [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]]\n| term_start = 18 August 2018\n| term_end =\n| president = [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]\n| predecessor = [[Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m]]\n| successor =\n| order1 = [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Culture and Tourism]]\n| term_start1 = 19 July 2017\n| term_end1 = 10 July 2018\n| 1blankname1 =\n| 1namedata1 =\n| primeminister1 = [[Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Nabi Avc\u0131]]\n| successor1 = [[Mehmet Nuri Ersoy]]\n| order2 = [[Deputy Prime Minister of Turkey]]\n| term_start2 = 24 May 2016\n| term_end2 = 19 July 2017\n| 1blankname2 =\n| 1namedata2 = \n| primeminister2 = [[Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Numan Kurtulmu\u015f]]\n| successor2 = [[Bekir Bozda\u011f]]\n| order3 = [[Deputy Prime Minister of Turkey]]\n| term_start3 = 24 May 2016\n| term_end3 = 19 July 2017\n| 1blankname3 =\n| 1namedata3 = \n| primeminister3 = [[Ahmet Davuto\u011flu]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Emrullah \u0130\u015fler]]\n| successor3 = [[Numan Kurtulmu\u015f]]\n| order4 = [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey#Composition|Member of the Grand National Assembly]]\n| term_start4 = 8 July 2018\n| term_end4 = \n| constituency4 = [[\u0130stanbul (electoral districts)|\u0130stanbul]] [[\u0130stanbul (3rd electoral district)|(III)]] ([[2018 Turkish general election|2018]])\n| term_start5 = 7 June 2015\n| term_end5 = 24 June 2018\n| constituency5 = [[Ordu (electoral district)|Ordu]] ([[June 2015 Turkish general election|June 2015]], [[November 2015 Turkish general election|Nov 2015]])\n| order6 = [[People's Voice Party|Leader of the People's Voice Party]]\n| term_start6 = 1 November 2010\n| term_end6 = 19 September 2012\n| predecessor6 = ''Position established''\n| successor6 = ''Position abolished''\n| order7 = [[Felicity Party|Leader of the Felicity Party]]\n| term_start7 = 26 October 2008\n| term_end7 = 17 October 2010\n| predecessor7 = [[Recai Kutan]]\n| successor7 = [[Necmettin Erbakan]]\n| signature = \n| website = [http://www.numankurtulmus.com.tr/ numankurtulmus.com.tr/]\n| cabinet = [[First Davuto\u011flu Cabinet|62nd]], [[2015 interim election government of Turkey|63rd]], [[Third Davuto\u011flu Cabinet|64th]], [[Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m Cabinet|65th]]\n}}\n'''Numan Kurtulmu\u015f''' (born 23 March 1959) is a Turkish politician and [[academician]]. [[Deputy chairman]] of [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]].\n\nHe served as [[Deputy Prime Minister of Turkey]] in the 62. 63. 64. 65. [[AK Party]] governments between 2014 and 2017 and [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Culture and Tourism]] between 2017 and 2018. Previously he served as the leader of [[Felicity Party]] between 2008 and 2010 and [[People's Voice Party]] between 2010 and 2012.\n\n== Personal life ==\n=== Family ===\nKurtulmu\u015f was born in [[\u00dcnye]] district of [[Ordu Province]]. He is of [[Georgians in Turkey|Georgian]] descent by his grandmother.<ref name>[http://www.istanbulunyehaber.com/etiket/siyaset//76/ \u0130stanbul \u00dcnye Haber]</ref> His grandfather Numan Kurtulmu\u015f who served as a major in the [[Turkish War of Independence]] on the [[\u00c7anakkale]], [[Erzurum]], [[Batumi]] and [[Azerbaijan]] fronts and fought in the [[Balkans]] and the [[Battle of Sakarya]] then later has injured and retired as a [[veteran]].<ref>[https://www.sabah.com.tr/numan-kurtulmus Biyografi \u2013 Sabah]</ref> He is also the author of Faith Commentary, known as the first [[Turkish language|Turkish]] religious guide which written by the [[latin alphabet]].<ref>[https://www.akparti.org.tr/ak-kadro/myk/numan-kurtulmus/ Biyografi \u2013 AK Parti]</ref> His father is Dr. Ismail Niyazi Kurtulmu\u015f. He currently resides in [[Fatih]] district of [[Istanbul]] with his family.\n\nHe married to Sevgi Kurtulmu\u015f in 1988. Children: Ay\u015fe, \u0130smail and Emir. He speaks fluent English. A fan of [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K.|Fenerbah\u00e7e FC]].<ref>[https://www.internethaber.com/numan-kurtulmus Numan Kurtulmu\u015f \u2013 \u0130nternethaber]</ref>\n\n=== Education and Academic career ===\nHe studied at Istanbul Imam Hatip High School, [[bachelor]] in 1982 and [[master degree]] in 1984 at [[Istanbul University]] Faculty of Business Administration.\n\nHe had been United States of America to the postgraduate studies at [[Temple University]] School of Business & Management in 1988\u20131989.\n\nHe was also a [[visiting researcher]] at [[Cornell University]] New York State School of Industrial & Labor Relations between 1990 and 1993. He got a PhD title from [[Istanbul University]] in 1992. Became an [[associate professor]] in 1994 and promoted to [[professorship]] in 2004 at [[Istanbul University]] [[Faculty of Economics]].<ref>[http://www.milliyet.com.tr/Siyaset/SonDakika.aspx?aType=SonDakika&Kategori=siyaset&KategoriID=&ArticleID=1005416&Date=20.10.2008&b=Erdogana%20entelektuel%20rakip Tayyip Erdo\u011fan\u2019a entelekt\u00fcel rakip \u2013 Milliyet Gazetesi]</ref> He was the [[assistant]] of [[Sabahattin Zaim]], who known as a 'the great professor'.<ref>[https://www.iyv.org.tr/tr/haberler/36/sabahattin-zaim-anma-gecesi.html Sabahattin Zaim Gecesi \u2013 \u0130YC]</ref>\n\nHe taught politics, [[labor economics]] and [[human resources management]] at [[Istanbul University]] Faculty of Economics and economics and [[political communication]] at [[Istanbul Commerce University]]. He also participated as a speaker in symposiums and seminars.\n\n=== Books ===\nHe's authored two books \"Post-Industrial Transformation\" and \"The Japanese Human Resource Management\".  Published master degree and Phd thesis on 'Integration of Inventory Management by the Database Approach' and 'The change of Industrial Relations for Terms of Model Human Type', also with many articles.\n\n== Political career ==\n[[File:High-level Meeting of the Ministers of Tourism of the EU member states \"Tourism and economic growth\" Handshake (38428157830).jpg|thumb|Numan Kurtulmu\u015f meets Minister of Tourism of Bulgaria [[Nikolina Angelkova]], 2018]]\nHe was kicked-off politic on [[Virtue Party]] in 1998. The party has been shutted down by [[Constitutional Court]] and he joined [[Felicity Party]]. Elected as chairman at the [[party congress]] held in 2008 and has been here until 2010.  Leaded establishing the [[People's Voice Party]] (HAS Party) in 2010. Upon the proposal of [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]] and [[People's Voice Party|HAS Party]] united in 2012. Within the framework of this combination, HAS Party has been terminated itself and Kurtulmu\u015f joined AK Party with many people.\n\n=== Virtue Party (1998\u20132001) ===\nIn 1998, he began the political career with [[Necmettin Erbakan]] and served as the chairman in [[Istanbul]] and a Member of the Main Administrative Board. When ended [[Virtue Party]], he joined the [[Felicity Party]] in 2001.\n\n=== Felicity Party (2001\u20132010) ===\nHe served as chairman in Istanbul and Deputy Chairman of Party until 2008 at [[Felicity Party]]. [[Recai Kutan]] who Chairman of Felicity Party announced on 17 October 2008 that Numan Kurtulmu\u015f will be [[candidate]] in the party congress to be held in Ankara on 26 October 2008.<ref>[http://www.internethaber.com/news_detail.php?id=161580 \u0130\u015fte Saadet'in yeni lideri \u2013 \u0130nternet Haber]</ref><ref>[http://www.haber7.com/haber/20081016/Saadet-Partisi-son-kararini-verdi.php Saadet Partisi, son karar\u0131n\u0131 verdi! \u2013 Haber 7]</ref><ref>[http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/10076179.asp?gid=233&sz=51524 Saadet Partisi\u2019nde Kurtulmu\u015f d\u00f6nemi \u2013 H\u00fcrriyet Gazetesi]</ref> The slogan was \"Felicity Now!\" And he was elected as a Chairman of [[Felicity Party]] by all valid 924 vote of the used 946 at 3rd Party Congress held in Ankara Atat\u00fcrk Sports Hall.<ref>[http://www.milligazete.com.tr/haber/sahit-olun-tarih-yaziliyor-82499.htm \u015eahit olun!.. tarih yaz\u0131l\u0131yor \u2013 Milli Gazete]</ref><ref>[http://haber.gazetevatan.com/haberdetay.asp?detay=Kutan_veda_etti_205610_9&tarih=27.10.2008&Newsid=205610&Categoryid=9  Kutan veda etti \u2013 Vatan Gazetesi]</ref><ref>[http://yenisafak.com.tr/Politika/?t=27.10.2008&i=146965 Kurtulmu\u015f'tan vira Bismillah \u2013 Yeni \u015eafak Gazetesi]</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he had divergency with Necmettin Erbakan who the leader of the Milli G\u00f6r\u00fc\u015f Movement. Numan Kurtulmu\u015f was re-elected as Chairman of Party, participating as just one candidate of the two lists at the 4th Party Congress held in Ankara on 11 July 2010. Numan Kurtulmu\u015f was participated the Election of Main Administrative Board with the white list against Necmettin Erbakan's green list. And the winner white list meant to be kicking Necmettin Erbakan and his friends out.<ref>[https://www.milliyet.com.tr/siyaset/saadet-iki-parca-1262780 Saadet iki par\u00e7a \u2013 Milliyet]</ref>\n\nAnd then later 650 delegates asked congress again, but this request was rejected by Party's General Administrative Board. Upon the decision appointment of the congress call committee by the court, 53 chairman, 65 mayors and many politician left Felicity Party on 1 October 2010.<ref>[http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/n.php?n=turkish-conservative-party-leader-resigns-2010-10-01 H\u00fcrriyet Daily News \u2013 Felicity Party]</ref>\n\nKurtulmu\u015f announced a new political movement, calls Civilization Politics Movement.<ref name=star>[http://www.stargazete.com/politika/adini-koydu-medeniyet-siyaseti-haber-299445.htm Ad\u0131n\u0131 koydu: Medeniyet siyaseti \u2013 Star]</ref>\n\n=== People's Voice Party (2010\u20132012) ===\n[[File:Numan Kurtulmu\u015f \u0130smail Heniye.jpeg|thumb|Numan Kurtulmu\u015f meets Prime Minister of Palestine [[Ismail Haniyeh]], 2012]]\n235 politician who united around Civilization Politics Movement announced that founded the [[People's Voice Party]] (HAS Party) on 1 November 2010.<ref>[http://www.cnnturk.com/2010/turkiye/10/31/kurtulmusun.partisi.hazir.halkin.sesi/594861.0/ Kurtulmu\u015f'un partisi haz\u0131r: \"Halk\u0131n Sesi\" \u2013 CNN T\u00fcrk]</ref> And Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as Chairman of Party by the 207 vote of 210 delegates<ref>[https://www.haberturk.com/gundem/haber/575684-has-parti-1-olagan-kongresi HAS Parti 1. Ola\u011fan Kongresi \u2013 Habert\u00fcrk]</ref> at the 1st Party Congress held in Ankara Atat\u00fcrk Sports Hall on 28 November 2010 on the 28th day of the founded of HAS Party.<ref>[http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/n.php?n=has-party-halted-its-first-convention-2010-11-28 H\u00fcrriyet Daily News \u2013 People's Voice Party]</ref>\n\n==== Combination process ====\nChairman of [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AK Party]] and Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] offered Kurtulmu\u015f to combinate AK Party with HAS Party on 12 July 2012.<ref>[http://yenisafak.com.tr/Politika/?t=12.07.2012&c=2&i=394245&k=f2 Ba\u015fbakan Erdo\u011fan resmen teklif etti \u2013 Yeni \u015eafak]</ref> According to the decision taken by the authorized persons of two sides and combination process has started.<ref>[http://siyaset.milliyet.com.tr/suleyman-soylu-da-ak-partide/siyaset/siyasetdetay/15.08.2012/1581241/default.htm S\u00fcleyman Soylu da AK Parti'de \u2013 Milliyet]</ref> HAS Party invited the delegates and dissolved itself at the extraordinary congress held in 19 September 2012 by 165 votes of the current 177 delegates according to the decision of combination.<ref>[http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/hsp-dissolves-itself-as-its-leader-plans-to-join-the-ruling-party.aspx?pageID=238&nID=30540&NewsCatID=33 H\u00fcrriyet Daily News \u2013 HAS Party Dissolves]</ref>\n\n=== Justice and Development Party (2012\u2013Current) ===\nAfter the HAS Party's termination, Kurtulmu\u015f joined [[AK Party]] at a ceremony held in [[\u0130stanbul]] on 22 September 2012 with many people.<ref>[http://www.haberturk.com/gundem/haber/778770-erdogan-yuvaniza-hos-geldiniz Numan Kurtulmu\u015f resmen AK Parti'li \u2013 Habert\u00fcrk]</ref> \n\n\u2013 Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as a Member of Main Administrative Board at 4th [[AK Party]] Congress held in Ankara on 30 September 2012, was appointed as vice chairman of party on the economy politics.<ref>[http://www.haber7.com/ic-politika/haber/936265-ak-partide-yeni-yonetim-kadrosu AK Parti'de yeni y\u00f6netim kadrosu \u2013 Haber7]</ref>\n\n\u2013 When Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] was elected as [[President of Turkey]] at [[presidential elections]] in 2014, [[Ahmet Davuto\u011flu]] replaced himself as a Prime Minister and Kurtulmu\u015f became [[Deputy Prime Minister]] at [[First Davuto\u011flu Cabinet|62nd]] Government.<ref>[http://www.haberturk.com/gundem/haber/985009-yeni-kabine-aciklandi Yeni Kabine A\u00e7\u0131kland\u0131 \u2013 Habert\u00fcrk]</ref>\n\n\u2013 Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as the [[Ordu]] [[parliamentarian]] in the elections of June 2015 and became [[Deputy Prime Minister]] and Spokesperson again at the [[2015 interim election government of Turkey|63rd]] Government under Ahmet Davuto\u011flu's Prime Ministry.<ref>[https://www.ntv.com.tr/galeri/turkiye/63-hukumette-yer-alan-isimler,xWMLJkRD7EOtukQkJxOZyw/rnSZm3ePPUyvVA-bVRcpDw 63. H\u00fck\u00fcmet'te yer alacak isimler \u2013 NTV]</ref>\n\n\u2013 Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as the [[Ordu]] parliamentarian again in the elections of November 2015, became [[Deputy Prime Minister]] and Spokesperson again at [[Third Davuto\u011flu Cabinet|64th]] Government under Ahmet Davuto\u011flu's Prime Ministry.<ref>[http://www.ahaber.com.tr/gundem/2015/11/24/numan-kurtulmus-yine-basbakan-yardimcisi Numan Kurtulmu\u015f yine ba\u015fbakan yard\u0131mc\u0131s\u0131 \u2013 aHaber]</ref>\n\n\u2013 Ahmet Davuto\u011flu when resigned prime ministry [[President Erdogan]] gave the government formation duty to [[Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m]]. Kurtulmu\u015f served as deputy prime minister again at [[Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m Cabinet|65th]] Government under Binali Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m's Prime Ministry. After a while held in 19 July 2017 he became [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Minister of Culture and Tourism]] in cabinet overhaul.<ref>[https://www.milliyet.com.tr/yerel-haberler/ankara/numan-kurtulmus-kultur-ve-turizm-bakani-oldu-12174905 Numan Kurtulmu\u015f K\u00fclt\u00fcr ve Turizm Bakan\u0131 \u2013 Milliyet]</ref>\n\n\u2013 Kurtulmu\u015f was elected as a parliamentarian of Istanbul on 24 June 2018 and became [[Deputy chairman]] of [[AK Party]] at the 6th AK Party Congress on 18 August 2018.<ref>[https://www.yenisafak.com/gundem/erdoganin-koltugu-kurtulmusa-emanet-3390873 Numan Kurtulmu\u015f Genel Ba\u015fkan Vekili \u2013 Yeni \u015eafak]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://twitter.com/NumanKurtulmus\n\n{{65th government of Turkey}}\n{{64th government of Turkey}}\n{{63rd government of Turkey}}\n{{Cabinet Davuto\u011flu}}\n{{SP Leaders}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kurtulmus, Numan}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from \u00dcnye]]\n[[Category:Turkish people of Georgian descent]]\n[[Category:Virtue Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Felicity Party politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Voice Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Turkish economists]]\n[[Category:Istanbul University alumni]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 25th Parliament of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 63rd government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Istanbul University faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the 26th Parliament of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 64th government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Deputy Prime Ministers of Turkey]]\n\n\n{{Turkey-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBooks:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: master degree \u2192 master's degree", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numan_Kurtulmu%C5%9F"}
{"title_page": "Jim J. Bullock", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name= Jim J. Bullock\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|birth_name= James Jackson Bullock\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1955|02|9}}<ref name=desert_sun_20110123>{{cite news |url=http://www.mydesert.com/article/20110123/LIFESTYLES01/101220352/Jim-J-Bullock-plays-dual-role-Clown-HIV-survivor |newspaper=[[The Desert Sun]] |location=Palm Springs |first=Judith |last=Salkin |title=Jim J. Bullock plays dual role: Clown, HIV survivor |date=January 23, 2011 |accessdate=June 7, 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128072802/http://www.mydesert.com/article/20110123/LIFESTYLES01/101220352/Jim-J-Bullock-plays-dual-role-Clown-HIV-survivor |archivedate=January 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n|birth_place= [[Casper, Wyoming]], U.S.\n|other_names= Jm J. Bullock\n|occupation= Actor, comedian\n|years_active= 1980\u2013present\n|spouse=\n|website=\n}}\n'''James Jackson Bullock''' (born February 9, 1955), sometimes credited as '''Jim J. Bullock''' or '''Jm J. Bullock''', is an American [[actor]] and [[comedian]] of [[theatre|stage]], [[television program|television]] and [[film|motion pictures]].\n\n==Early life==\nBullock was born in [[Casper, Wyoming]], and raised in [[Odessa, Texas]] (although  he is listed as an alumnus of [[Natrona County High School]] ([[Casper, Wyoming]])), and was raised in a [[Southern Baptist Convention|Southern Baptist]] home and as a youth, planned to become an evangelical Christian minister.<ref name=desert_sun_20110123/> He received a music scholarship to attend [[Oklahoma Baptist University]] in [[Shawnee, Oklahoma]], but left school without graduating.<ref name=advocate_19990720>{{cite magazine| url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-55183037/the-comeback-kidder| magazine=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]| first=Bohdan| last=Zachary| title=The Comeback Kidder| date=July 20, 1999| accessdate=14 September 2018| via=[[Questia Online Library]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBullock became a notable entertainment figure in the 1980s when he co-starred on the [[Situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Too Close for Comfort]]'' as Monroe Ficus (credited as \"Jm J. Bullock\") and was a regular guest on [[John Davidson (entertainer)|John Davidson]]'s updated version of ''[[Hollywood Squares]]''; Bullock occasionally substituted for Davidson as host.<ref name=\"av140615\">{{cite news |first1=Marah |last1=Eakin |first2=John |last2=Teti |first3=Erik |last3=Adams |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]] |title=Bonus round stars: 9 celebrities who found their greatest fame on game shows |url=http://www.avclub.com/article/bonus-round-stars-9-celebrities-who-found-their-gr-205592 |date=June 16, 2014 |accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref> He also appeared as a semi-regular on ''[[Battlestars (game show)|Battlestars]]''. He later became a semi-regular on ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'' (from 1989 to 1990) as Neal Tanner. He guest-hosted a special episode of ''[[Double Dare (Nickelodeon game show)|Super Sloppy Double Dare]]'' in 1989 where host [[Marc Summers]] and announcer [[Harvey (announcer)|Harvey]] played against each other. The game ended with both Summers and Harvey playing the Obstacle Course and winning all eight prizes for their respective civilian teammates. Stage assistants Robin Marrella and Dave Shikiar guest-announced that episode.\n\nAfter ''ALF'' went off the air in 1990, Bullock remained active with [[theatre]], [[television]], and [[film]] work. He briefly hosted a syndicated [[talk show]] with ex-[[televangelist]] [[Tammy Faye Messner]]. The ''Jim J. and Tammy Faye Show'' debuted in 1996, but Messner exited the program a few months later following a cancer diagnosis. Bullock continued with new co-host, Ann Abernathy, and the show became ''The Jim J. and Ann Show'' until it was canceled.\n\nBullock was the voice of ''[[Queer Duck]]'' in the animated series of cartoons of the same name which have appeared on both the [[internet]] and the cable TV network [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]. In 2000, Bullock was a regular panelist on the revival of ''[[I've Got a Secret]]''. He also performed on the national tour of the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' as Wilbur Turnblad, a role he took to the Broadway stage starting September 18, 2007. Some of his other noteworthy roles include the pilled-up narcoleptic Prince [[Valium]] in the 1987 [[Mel Brooks]] movie ''[[Spaceballs]]'', and the \"Not-Quite-Out-of-the-Closet\" character in the date montage at the beginning of 2001's ''[[Kissing Jessica Stein]]''. From 2004 to 2007, he had a recurring role as Mr. Monroe, a teacher at the fictional James K. Polk Middle School on the [[Nickelodeon]] live action sitcom ''[[Ned's Declassified School Survival Guide]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1985, while ''Too Close For Comfort'' was being retooled as ''The Ted Knight Show'', Bullock learned that he was [[HIV]] positive. He made his diagnosis public 11 years later.<ref name=\"nydn\">{{cite news |last1=Sacks |first1=Ethan |title=Before Charlie Sheen, here are other celebrities whose HIV-positive diagnoses or contracting of AIDS shocked fans |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/celebrities-hiv-positive-aids-article-1.2436964 |accessdate=20 June 2019 |work=New York Daily News |date=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Bullock's partner of six years, John Casey, died from [[AIDS]]-related complications.<ref name=desert_sun_20110123/><ref name=advocate_19990720/>  Bullock is a longtime survivor of the virus and, as of 2018, was still healthy due in part to [[antiretroviral drug]]s.<ref name=desert_sun_20110123/><ref name=usatoday_20010606>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/spotlight/2001-06-06-bullock-aids.htm| newspaper=[[USA Today]]| first=Mike| last=Falcon| title=Jim J. Bullock reflects on AIDS anniversary| date=June 6, 2001| accessdate=January 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn February 17, 1999, Bullock was arrested outside a bar in [[West Hollywood, California]], for possession of [[crystal meth]], and was sentenced to probation.<ref name=advocate_19990720/><ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20131630,00.html| title=Too Close for Comfort: 1980-1985| magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]| date=26 June 2000| accessdate=18 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Genre !! width=\"60\" | Year !! Title !! Role !! Episodes !! Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1980\u20131987 || ''[[Too Close for Comfort]]'' || Monroe Ficus ||  || 118 episodes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |1981 || ''[[Full Moon High]]'' || Eddie ||  || credited as Jm. Bullock<br>Alternative title: ''Moon High''\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |1987 || ''[[Spaceballs]]'' || Prince Valium ||  || credited as JM J. Bullock\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |1988 || ''[[DeGarmo & Key]]: Rock Solid...The Rock-u-mentary!'' || News Reporter ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1989 || ''[[Super Sloppy Double Dare]]'' || Himself/Guest Host ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1989\u20131990 || ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'' || Neal Tanner || \"He Ain't Heavy, He's Willie's Brother\" <br/> \"The First Time Ever I Saw Your Face\" <br/> \"Break Up to Make Up\" <br/> \"Happy Together\"<br/> \"Love on the Rocks\" || {{hs|00}}5 episodes total\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |1991 || ''[[Switch (1991 film)|Switch]]'' || {{hs|Psychic}}The Psychic ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1992 || ''[[Seinfeld]]'' || Flight Attendant #1 || \"{{sortname|The|Airport}}\" || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n|Music Video|| align=\"center\" |1994|| ''[[Bubba Hyde]]'' || Bubba Hyde || \"[[Diamond Rio]] song\" ||\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1994\u20131995 || ''[[Boogies Diner]]'' || Gerald ||  || unknown episodes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Animated TV series || align=\"center\" |1994 || ''[[Duckman|Duckman: Private Dick/Family Man]]'' ||  || \"Cellar Beware\" || [[Voice acting|voice actor]]\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |1996 || ''[[Roseanne]]'' || Al || \"Satan, Darling\" || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Animated TV series || align=\"center\" |1999 || ''[[Queer Duck]]'' || Adam Seymour \"Queer Duck\" Duckstein ||  || [[Voice acting|voice actor]]; 20 episodes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |2000 || ''[[E! True Hollywood Story]]'' || Himself || \"Jim J. Bullock\" || documentary\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Documentary || align=\"center\" |2000 || ''{{sortname|The|Eyes of Tammy Faye}}'' || Himself ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |2000 || ''[[Get Your Stuff]]'' || Tom ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[10 Attitudes]]'' || Tex ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[Kissing Jessica Stein]]'' || Not-Yet-Out Gay Guy (Craig) ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Film || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[Circuit (film)|Circuit]]'' || Mark ||  || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[Intimate Portrait (TV series)|Intimate Portrait]]'' || Himself || \"Tammy Faye\" || documentary\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |2001 || ''[[Popular (TV series)|Popular]]'' || Judge || \"{{hs|Brain Game}}The Brain Game\" || \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Short film || align=\"center\" |2002 || ''[[Gaydar (film)|Gaydar]]'' || Maurice's Ex ||  || 20 minutes <br/> included in the [[Direct-to-video]] compilation film ''Men's Mix 1: Gay Shorts Collection''\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| TV series || align=\"center\" |2004 || ''[[Ned's Declassified School Survival Guide]]'' || Mr. Monroe || \"First Day & Lockers\" <br/> \"Bathrooms & Project Partners\" <br/> \"Teachers & Detention\" <br/> \"Seating & Tryouts\" <br/> \"Crushes and Dances\" <br/> \"Sick Days & Spelling Bee\" <br/> \"Rumors & Photo Day\" <b